the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E3vTSCzgrasNijUO]{Fleet Footed} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Red and White</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>14. Wissenland</h2>\n<p><strong>Recruit:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Wissenland)}</p>\n<p><strong>Soldier:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Ywo6fZNPC4zbHHSQ]{Strong-minded} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Sergeant:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Dwarfs)} Skill</p>\n<p><strong>Officer:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.wNvPXAhlKABl6hpk]{Pure Soul} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Grey and White</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.1M9tar1BLRAqhUwS"}}}
{"_id":"GiIApYNByyPAlXJu","name":"Divine Lore of Kislev","content":"<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\">Dazh, God of Fire and Hospitality</h2>\n<p>Dazh is the God of fire, the sun, and hospitality. He has been worshipped in the lands of Kislev for uncounted centuries and is believed to have taught early Ungol tribesmen the secrets of fire. Dazh is often comparable to Shallya in terms of benevolence and caring for his followers, and this attitude reflects strongly on the priests who worship him. Priests of Dazh are warm-hearted individuals who take deep pride in their hearts and homes, and many bedeck themselves in sacred gold. Those who call upon Dazh often prefer heat to cold and may feel uncomfortable when the sun sets.</p>\n<h3><strong>Dazh's Blessings and Strictures :</strong></h3>\n<table style=\"width: 99.0798%;\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 16.66%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.ElmLfnrXliStS9CP]{Battle}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.66%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.tEMwdlHM8A40h6HE]{Conscience}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 9.37318%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.Cg2Q3TV66cpmheHS]{Courage}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 23.7918%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.iIfYOlNrLb0uiV8c]{Fortune}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.815%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.K5DE9cceinUTIrem]{Protection}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.66%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.tMocig1z9dHKNiCT]{Wit}</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li>Never let a fire go out during the night. Many interpret this stricture as never leaving a fire unattended.</li>\n<li>Never light a fire on a dirty hearth.</li>\n<li>Always give hospitality to those who ask for it, even enemies. Leave none out in the cold.</li>\n<li>Offer sacrifices to Dazh on the first day of the winter snows, so he returns with all speed.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><strong>Miracles of Dazh</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.mfd2Q3F8oH7w8Pvp]{Blessing of Dazh}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.7qtCJzptXNrP3L8g]{Brilliance}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.9osSigWd5Tn4NAuS]{Dazh Szheg!}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.3eRsG3BvysAv0wjk]{Dance of the Alari}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.T0pWaZIrsUbmAUhv]{Gift of Fire}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.nDIYbSM4IoH2RdTH]{Rouse the Coals}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.eHp4Q1uh4F4TwXTo]{Sacred Guest}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.hpDFSYteYcuLWJdd]{Wreath of Flame}</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\">Tor, God of War and Thunder</h2>\n<p>Tor is the God of thunder, lightning, and war. He is popular amongst the war-like Kislevites and was worshipped in the area long before the Gospodars arrived. The Axe of Tor is a sacred symbol among the people of Kislev, as his influence is so powerful that even towns sacked by marauders are said to have their temples dedicated to Tor perfectly intact. It is theorized that even the foul servants of Chaos dare not tempt his wrath, for his reputation as a butcher of daemons and undead is so legendary, and his followers so full of vengeful fury, that it&rsquo;s a guaranteed death sentence to anger the ancient war god. Priests of Tor are often taciturn and belligerent, and many wield war axes detailed in sacred silver. Those who call upon Tor can be quick to anger, and many are drawn to high locations, such as mountains or tall towers. At the GM&rsquo;s whim, any use of Torinyi prayers involving thunder, lightning, or rain may bring on a full storm.</p>\n<h3><strong>Tor's Blessings and Strictures :</strong></h3>\n<table style=\"width: 99.0798%;\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 16.66%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.ElmLfnrXliStS9CP]{Battle}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.66%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.Cg2Q3TV66cpmheHS]{Courage}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 9.37318%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.0r3moMIHXsBrcOyh]{Hardiness}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 23.7918%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.KSDrXcieyRc37YI7]{Might}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.815%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.eBRjKAF6U0yR0KK8]{Savagery}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.66%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.GvaOlWY8iD5CO1WB]{Tenacity}</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li>Never stand under a tree during a thunderstorm.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><strong>Miracles of Tor</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.Kj16kz7MhUyglfWj]{Call of Tor}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.B8XYBARBek7wsdfa]{Cleave the Sky}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.eraiMWviMkD0rOWs]{Do Tor!}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.EgrP2ecMVHjOJXWu]{Incoming Storm}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.AVuXwKD8JpdWHZVA]{Thunder of War}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.LhrVlXwDApp0Zhcg]{Tor's Fury}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.ZYMpqR54q3J4V4Bv]{Wrath of Tor}</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\">Ursun, God of Bears and Strength</h2>\n<p>Ursun is the God of bears and patron of Kislev. His cult was introduced by the Gospodars almost a thousand years ago and is now the most powerful in the land. Priests of Ursun tend to be wild individuals, and many wear sacred skins and holy bear bones. The trails to becoming a priest of Ursun are brutal, with the most famous requiring an acolyte to wrestle a bear in the woods bare handed. Those calling upon Ursun are often uncomfortable around the trappings of civilization and frequently grow lethargic in winter. It is very common for Ursun priests, especially war priests, to travel into the same forests in which they first underwent the test to becoming a priest, reacquainting with the bear they wrestled with, and through various means, bond with them making the bear a valued ally, mount and friend.</p>\n<h3><strong>Ursun's Blessings and Strictures :</strong></h3>\n<table style=\"width: 99.0798%;\" border=\"1\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"width: 16.66%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.ElmLfnrXliStS9CP]{Battle}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.66%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.Cg2Q3TV66cpmheHS]{Courage}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 9.37318%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.0r3moMIHXsBrcOyh]{Hardiness}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 23.7918%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.By5dc8Q7ZAGpr177]{The Hunt}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.815%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.KSDrXcieyRc37YI7]{Might}</td>\n<td style=\"width: 16.66%; text-align: center;\">@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.2WN0muIB2BFd4kBO]{Righteousness}</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<ul>\n<li>Never hunt a bear in winter&mdash;let him sleep as he lets you sleep.</li>\n<li>Wake the bear in the spring, and feed him well before his winter rests.</li>\n<li>Bears must only be killed by the strength of your hand or the flight of an arrow.</li>\n<li>Only display the hide, claw, tooth, or skull of a bear you have killed yourself.</li>\n<li>Shun the comforts of indoor life whenever possible. In particular, all ablutions and bathing must be done outdoors.</li>\n<li>Eat fish at least once a week, as the bear does. Never eat fish and another meat on the same day, as this is wasteful.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><strong>Miracles of Ursun</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.4jCnBsAX6gmPYuVE]{Blessing of the Licked Paw}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.QvoHl9J279WEc0Bj]{Blessing of Ursun}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.LgPbA88zKlxhXtQp]{Father Bear}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.DgPoRHIETTKaTsHI]{Growling Fury}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.zrlPnsVUnxXp652U]{Skin of the Ice Bear}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.qeskYySyElYLfMRP]{Unyielding Ursun}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.GCbkVVvi4657fR55]{Ursine Strength}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.prayers-nom.De4GiKFo2z97CC7M]{Winter's Sleep}</li>\n</ul>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.FWO7epVNCOKTqJxY"}}}
{"_id":"LZ4S1NP0dQZeQqWL","name":"Lore of Ice","permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.kA5BGlSrRt9nxUIe"}},"content":"<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Lore of Ice</h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Ice Magic, also known as the Lore of Ice, is Kislev&rsquo;s oldest magical tradition, dating back many centuries before the Empire founded the Colleges of Magic under Magnus the Pious, and exclusively wielded by women of Kislev sensitive to the Winds of Magic. Before invading Kislev in 1497 IC under the Khan-Queen Miska, the first Ice Witches practiced their magic on the Endless Steppe. Unlike their former brethren, the Hung and Kurgan&mdash;who worshipped the Great Eye after falling to Chaos&mdash;the Gospodars learned to tap the cold power coursing through the land itself, establishing a relationship not too dissimilar with the Jade Order and their ties to nature. The ice witches of Kislev are more than just women with the ability to channel the Ancient Widow&rsquo;s cold flows; they are an organized sisterhood who works together to achieve shared goals under the orders of the Tzar/Tzarina of Kislev. Although this magic does not carry the same risks of mutation as magics of Chaos, it is very difficult to control and often kills unwary and inexperienced Witches. Many centuries later, things are little different. As should be expected for a magic with its roots in wars on the Endless Steppe, Ice Magic is deadly and extremely so, not just for the Witches&rsquo; enemies but for the Witches themselves. Many apprentice Witches do not survive their training; indeed, some can be found to this day in isolated corners of the Oblast, frozen eternally as sparkling statues of ice by the magic they failed to control. Ice witches can often be found wearing heavy winters clothes with fur coats, capes and boots (even in hotter climates) with older and more experienced ice witches wearing crowns of ice on their heads.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Lore Attribute:</strong> The flows of Ice Magic vary in strength. By Kislev&rsquo;s sites of power, along her leylines, in freezing climates and in the depths of winter, Ice Magic is very strong, granting you a +10 to all Channeling and Language Magick Tests when casting the Lore of Ice. But in warmer climes, it is far weaker and wanes the closer to the equator and the further from the North one travels. When casting in warmer climates, such as in most of the Empire, it counts as if casting next to a Corrupting Influence, causing a Minor Miscast on a unit&rsquo;s roll of an 8. If you already have a Minor Miscast, the Miscast becomes a Major Miscast. In hotter climates, such as in a desert or jungle, you receive a permanent Fatigued Condition until you relocate to a cooler climate. You may spend a Resolve point to mitigate this Fatigue Condition for one round.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Ingredients:</strong> Ice of all types, from snowflakes, hailstones, icicles and carved ice sculptures, comprise the majority of the Lore of Ice&rsquo;s ingredients. While plentiful in the cold lands of Kislev, due to their frozen nature, it is potentially much more difficult to acquire or preserve these ingredients needed depending on the region, climate and time of year. However, many spells also use trappings associated with the body parts of certain wildlife within Kislev, including the claws of a frostfiend, a ball of bear fat, fangs of a white dragon or the tongue of a hawk.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Spells:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.qgdwGhYIaGYWR6h9]{Biting Wind}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.pOql6YVNBt21t13s]{Blizzard}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.mqktfTIQDkgycvwc]{Chill}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.qu4My8KV2Wq9LPRM]{Chill Voice}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.c0DM4WCtLftKxDPd]{Crystal Cloak}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.8xcqDJycW7O9OOP4]{Death Frost}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.sSMen3XXCY2jZ2CV]{Form of the Frostfiend}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.mqkBtPUX7NEF0ouV]{Frost Blade}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.UXHgHKjAUAa27zfc]{Hailstorm}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.c2kGYd5oOCO9XqVR]{Hawks of Miska}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.2DO6nDvYhzI9ajKg]{Ice Maiden's Kiss}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.HL4p2CRTTshAczbK]{Ice Sheet}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.4IxkhraDM0cYmEr7]{Permafrost}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.nlG5zkUTh1uNTSu2]{Shardstorm}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.Tcgfdb7iVdo6Dc8i]{Shoika's Call}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.vMb9P8WdJRebN93m]{Walk the Endless Steppe}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.9GeKCw8XW2zRcb4L]{Wall of Ice}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.spells-nom.qCuzgwOb45ybYZaQ]{Winter Walk}</li>\n</ul>"}
{"_id":"LbGZ2HZlxeSGJoIm","name":"Provinces of the Empire","content":"<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Provinces of the Empire</h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Averland</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Hochland</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Middenland</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Nordland</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Ostermark</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Ostland</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Reikland</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Stirland</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Sylvania</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Talabecland</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Wissenland</strong></h3>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"averland\">1. Averland</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The people of Averland are curious folk. Folk whisper the proud bloodline of the Brigundians has somewhat curdled with time, inbreeding, and the looming influence of the Black Mountains. At their best, Averlanders are open, passionate, and honest about just what they're thinking. If a funeral happens to strike them as funny, well, they'll laugh. If someone upsets them, they'll let you know. Known to be generous, especially when entertaining, Averlanders prize those skilled at the art of telling tall stories, something wandering entertainers are very glad of. Dwarfs are also very welcomed in Averland as their plain talking ways are much admired.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>At their worst Averlanders are contradictory, flighty, and changeable. Astrology and other such superstitions are very popular in Averland, and merchants will often ditch a deal made in \"an unfavoruable hour\" or on an \"unlucky day.\" Marius Leitdorf, known for his dark depression and strange rages, was considered typical of the Averland temperment. Even Trollslayers have been heard to say that Averlanders are \"a bit odd in the head.\" Their changeable nature has resulted in many jokes about regiments of Averlanders retreating in the face of fear, something that irritates them to no end. They resent any implication that their martial prowess is any less than that of any other states. Averlanders are also known for their intolerance of lawyers and contracts, as they imply a man might change his mind. Those dealing with Averlanders are constantly irritated with their insistence that everything be done \"on honour\" - particularly given their unreliable reputation. Some whisper this \"whim of iron\" is in fact a cunning bargaining tool of the Averland merchants.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Averlanders have a strange, almost \"sing-song\" element to their speech. They tend to soften harsh words and elongate vowels. Many artists and young nobles with pretensions to poetry imitate an Averlander accent, in a belief that all great geniuses are touched by madness.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup> &nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.4IGdIhnwTaZijzg7]{Charm Animal}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.0CwV96kTDRF0jUhk]{Entertain (Speeches)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.5EvSIh1khpt77uM7]{Language (Bretonnian)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XzPlUWFDtOOjG98P]{Language (Khazalid)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Cg2b92BRjvxYXZiE]{Language (Mootish)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oMaJZ5cvCJeOUq9H]{Leadership}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Averland)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oSbEE6eXH1S3LfUU]{Ride (Horse)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.wKwel9MG7NIG3i3w]{Trade (Farmer)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fn8QNQQ1S2rh12Us]{Doomed}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E98mVLZgE8bX5vQW]{Hatred (Greenskins}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Dwarfs}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>One @Table[talents]</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"hochland\">2. Hochland</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Hochland is a small but proud province, famed for its hunters and trackers. The Hochlanders' traditional dish of fired venison has been exported across the Empire, but gourmands say it still tastes best cooked under the night sky of Hochland. At their best, Hochlanders are loyal, valiant, and adaptable. <sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Present-day Hochlanders are amongst the most open minded and friendly people in the Empire. With their lands being a crossroad for so much of the northern and eastern Empire, they have developed tolerance that is considered unusual everywhere else in the realm.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Though mainly worshippers of Taal, Rhya, and of Sigmar, contact with travellers and merchants using the roads has made Ulric popular in the northeast, while Shallya also has a strong cult. Contact with educated outsiders has led to a respect for intellectuals, so much so that the rulers of Hergig encouraged the founding of a private academy and even a small school of wizardry.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Recognising their lands are unsuited to large-scale farming or cattle-raising, the people of Hochland have done what they can to encourage others to visit and leave some of their money behind. Shrines to several cults can be found in most towns and villages, each claiming to be the site of a miracle and having blessed relics for sale.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Fortified coaching inns sprang up along the roads for the convenience of travelers, though several had been bought by the rival Tunnelway and Wolf Runners coaching company. Fond of hunting in all its form, tales of loyal friendship and jaunty ballads, Hochlanders are also known to be easily distracted by the prospect of little sport.Some folk of other Imperial provinces also whisper that the Hochlanders' valiant nature is due more to their naivety than any innate loyalty. Jokes about Hoclanders who love their bow or rifle more then their wives are common, though most are too rude to repeat.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>This dedication to marksmanship has resulted in the excellent Hochland long rifle regiments that have proved so useful in recent times as part of the Imperial military. The Hochland spirit is said to resist defeatism in all its forms, \"Even unto Death\" as is the Hochlander motto. In recent years, however, much has happened to change the normally optimistic, trusting Hochlander character.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Forum</strong><sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Hochland)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.os4NKy5Oy6sRt1eh]{Outdoor Survival}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Fs06sr7y9JKpVQmB]{Perception}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.H2upcZ7q7qAPtPic]{Ranged (Blackpowder)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZQSm2AwrgT2cHG0C]{Ranged (Bow)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.bVdhLdfuSAfMi3qq]{Secret Signs (Hunters)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Xk5tp3aasPNtk4zt]{Stealth (Rural)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rt2rGSwFDCDHPh0A]{Track}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fn8QNQQ1S2rh12Us]{Doomed}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.q58lK4kULJZB5GjE]{Rover}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.5lcttqGToT54WFrl]{Marksman}<em> or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.oQzTJEXUx28sCiH3]{Sharp}, Three @Table[talents]</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"middenland\">3. Middenland</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Like all Northerners, Middenlanders are famed for their stubborn ways. This, their Teutogen blood and their &ldquo;firebrand&rdquo; tempers has given them a reputation as uncontrollable traditionalists. They hate change of all types, and defend what they see as &ldquo;tradition&rdquo; at all cost. They are the last to admit that they are wrong, and the first to challenge an unworthy leader. Whilst those of southern Middenland are less strident than their Drakwald cousins, even they are considered coarse, arrogant, and controlling by the rest of the Empire. At their best, Middenlanders are staunch defenders of pride, property and traditions. Should an unjust tax be levied, Middenlanders will march in protest, torches flaming and pitchforks raised. They can sometimes rally behind a single person&rsquo;s case, particularly those of destitute war widows, orphans and put upon guild members.</p>\n<p>This has caused Middenland politics to have a crude, rabble-rousing element that does not exist so much in other provinces. At their worst, Middenlanders are a fractious, intolerant group of individuals. Not only are they quick to mock those they see as foppish, dandified folk, they are also exceedingly suspicious of foreign influence upon their province. They refuse to use the occasional Bretonnian, Tilean, or Estalian words that have been absorbed into Reikspiel. Ordering a Bretonnian brandy in a Middenland Tavern will cause a yawning silence as all the folk look round at the fool who has just signed his own death warrant.</p>\n<p>Middenlanders are divided along what were once boundaries of ancient Teutogen Clans, but have now been divided into geographical prejudices. At one time the Drakwald region had a distinct identity from the rest of Middenland, producing a line of notoriously corrupt Emperors. With the collapse of their dynasty and the devastation of the Great Plague of 1111, the power of the Drakwald was decimated. It ceased to exist as a separate entity when the Emperor Mandred gave it to Middenheim, creating the province as it stands today. Its people are still known as mean-spirited and grasping but seem to be softening over time and incorporated into the Middenlander people.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The rules for creating a Middenlander or a Middenheimer character are described page 151 &amp; 152 of the official Supplement <strong>Middenheim: City of the White Wolf.</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"nordland\">4. Nordland</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The people of Nordland are descendents of the ancient <em>Was Jutone</em> tribe. Close brothers to the Udoses and Was Jutones tribe of Ostland, the Nordland branch of the tribe eventually became estranged from the more easterly settlements of their peoples. Eventually the early Nordlanders fell in battle, becoming vassals of the belligerent Teutogens, and frequent victims of Norscan raids. During the chaos that reigned in the aftermath of the Great Plague, much of Nordland's coast was invaded and colonised by the Norscans, leading to a mingling of the tribal bloodlines. Emperor Mandred Ratslayer, faced with graver threats elsewhere, had little time to answer the pleas of the Nordlanders, much to their horror.</p>\n<p>As time passed and populations mixed, the Nordlanders adopted many of the customs of their Norscan cousins. Courts frequently resort to trial of combat, the contest taking place on a white sheet pegged to the ground. The first person to stain the sheet red with his blood is declared the loser and the guilty party. Older houses often have runes carved into their doors and window frames for luck and spiritual protection, and along the coast the longhouse style is still common. At feasts and gatherings, Norscan bragging contests have evolved into more genteel storytelling events, with each speaker trying to outdo the last.</p>\n<p>So great is the Nordlanders love of stories that they have become famous around the Empire as great storytellers. The folk of this province are said to be amongst the loudest and frankest of all the empire. They seem to lack any subtlety, tact, or common sense. Several local legends involve heroes who blurt out the truth at the vital moments, thus saving the day. Other provinces point out this is because Nordlanders are too stupid to lie. At their best Nordlanders are solid, straightforward, and honest folk, looking down upon (while lacking the guile of) the mealy mouthed words of politicians, poets, and soft Reiklanders.</p>\n<p>At their worst, Nordlanders are churlish, uncouth, thoughtless speakers. Even the merchants of Nordland have this blunt approach, though they seem to be fine with double-dealings. Indeed they have found that shouting the final price has a profound effect upon merchants used to the subtleties of barter and negotiation. Many provinces point out that this is because of their mongrel <em>Was Jutone</em>, <em>Teutogen</em>, and <em>Norscan </em>Bloodlines. This mixed of heritage has been a source of Nordlander shame for many generations. Modern Imperials look on Norscans with a mixture of admiration and fear, seeing them both as powerful warriors and wild, uncivilized barbarians, not to be trusted around one's daughters or sheep. A popular Imperial saying runs \"<em>Character is in the blood</em>\", meaning the ancestry determines character.</p>\n<p>Thus the Nordlanders are often regarded as \"Not quite like us\" rougher and more uncouth even more so than the wild and hairy Middenlanders. Another case of discomfort among Nordlanders comes form their current fashion among nobles especially in the north, for tracing ancestry back to one of the founding tribes. The purer the background the higher ones status climbs, and the summit is the tracing of a lineage back to one of the founding chiefs. Alone amongst the provinces, the Nordlanders ancestors were conquered by outsiders, which is a source of embarrassment for status-conscious nobles, particularly when dealing with arrogant Middenlanders and Stirlander bumkpins.</p>\n<p>To compensate, most Nordlanders are more vocally and demonstratively loyal to the Empire and the Cult of Ulric than almost anyone else in the empire. Their efforts ring hollow to some, while others see them as examples of duty and patriotism. Whatever the motive, there is no doubting their bravery in battle. When in an army with troops from other provinces, Nordlanders are rash in their desire to close with the enemy. At the <a class=\"new\" title=\"Battle of Frote (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvQmF0dGxlX29mX0Zyb3RlP2FjdGlvbj1lZGl0JnJlZGxpbms9MQ==\">Battle of Frote</a> in 2421 IC, the Nordland pikes were so anxious to come to grips with the forces of Chaos that they charged before an order was given, leaving them isolated on the battlefield and their own army's flank exposed. Since then imperial generals have been quietly advised to treat the Nordlanders \"as they would a hound on a leash\" - to keep them under control.</p>\n<p>Renowned hunters and foresters, the Nordlanders woodland skills are so strong that even Hochlanders and the folk of the Talabec will grudgingly admit that they are \"not too bad\". Certainly Nordlanders are close to the land: the province has one of the largest communites of Rhya worship in the North of the Empire centred around the clannish villages south of Hargendorf. The Worship of the Harvest Mother without her consort Taal, is considered particularly dangerous in some circles of thought. Talabeclanders in particular are dismissive of this \"women worship\". They whisper that the Elves join the Humans for their religious rites at old stone circles deep in the woods, though speculation is rife, so no-one knows what really goes on in these ceremonies. The Elector Count is not comfortable with this, and is considering sending investigators to determine if the people of the <a class=\"new\" title=\"Demst Vale (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvRGVtc3RfVmFsZT9hY3Rpb249ZWRpdCZyZWRsaW5rPTE=\">Demst Vale</a> are planning a revolt. A Nordlander's accent is one of the most distinctive of the Empire. Their speech is very harsh and fast, almost barked out rather then spoken.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The rules for creating a Nordlander character are described page 153 of the official Supplement <strong>Middenheim: City of the White Wolf.</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"ostermark\">5. Ostermark</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Ostermarkers tend to be stout and thickset, and their eyes often reveal an Eastern heritage brought by the Ungols long ago. Their men are given to wearing long, thick moustaches rather than beards, and a high-peaked fur hat replaces the more fashionable floppy headgear found elsewhere in the Empire. Women wear their hair loose if single, or in a long braid wound up at the back of the head if married. Because of the cold weather, Ostermarkers tend to wear several layers of clothing in a style that seems quaint or old-fashioned to others in the Empire.&nbsp;At their best, Ostermarkers are vibrant souls, with a love of life, horses, vodka, and dancing. Their women in particular are known for their quick tempers and passionate nature. More than one Reiklander dandy has been dumped semi-naked on the Veldt after attempting to seduce a maid of Ostermark &mdash; often by the maid herself.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Few Empire folk naturally think of this side of the Ostermark nature, however. Most claim that Ostermarkers are half Kislevite, half peasant and entirely morose. Famed for long drinking binges, elaborate funerals, and combinations of the two, many people fear to ask an Ostermarker how their day has been, for fear of a depressing monologue.&nbsp;At their worst Ostermarkers show an almost theatrical obsession with death and its trappings. Women seldom remarry once widowed, for no Ostermark husband would stay in Morr&rsquo;s realm knowing another man was with his wife.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Fear of hauntings makes exorcists and priests of Morr very welcome throughout Ostermark, whilst carpenters are very much in demand to carve the elaborate coffins that are so common in this province. To an Ostermarker, this tradition of flamboyant despair is natural. Coming from a province that is regularly raided, destroyed, and plundered, they understand that death is a common part of life.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup>&nbsp; <strong>- Warhammer Forum</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.R2ytluHiEFF2KQ5e]{Consume Alcohol}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.CcNJsS4jSwB6Ug1J]{Endurance}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.I0yPc4PH5erWJLmu]{Intimidate}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.cYtU0ORRFCOpQLWz]{Intuition}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.EXysjCwmGzCOiRDx]{Language (Gospodarinyi)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Ungol)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oMaJZ5cvCJeOUq9H]{Leadership}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Ostermark)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.PzimjNx9Ojq4g6mV]{Melee (Polearm)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZQSm2AwrgT2cHG0C]{Ranged (Bow)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fn8QNQQ1S2rh12Us]{Doomed}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>One&nbsp;@Table[talents], @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.5lcttqGToT54WFrl]{Marksman}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.JLzJws09GMw9GWBV]{Coolheaded}, Three&nbsp;@Table[talents]</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"ostland\">6. Ostland</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Notoriously thrifty, Ostlanders are known for their ability to survive. Said to be capable of eating anything, there are several mocking songs about the famous &lsquo;Stone soup of Ostland&rsquo; They are so creative in their frugality that a common joke in the Empire claims that Ostlanders make &lsquo;stone soup&rsquo; with only one stone, for fear of wasting good rocks. While an exaggeration, it is true that Ostlanders are skilled in getting the most use out of what they have to work with and for being loath to throw anything away that might still be useful. This conservatism has at times cost them, as when <a class=\"new\" title=\"Von Raukov (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvVm9uX1JhdWtvdj9hY3Rpb249ZWRpdCZyZWRsaW5rPTE=\">von Raukov&rsquo;s</a> predecessors refused to adopt gunpowder weapons, because that would mean wasting perfectly good swords and spears. At their best, Ostlander are cool-headed in a crisis, practical, and not given to airs and graces. They are proud survivors, and teach their offspring to hold their heads high, despite the circumstances.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>At their worst, Ostlanders are overly stubborn, proud, and intolerant. They hate waste of all sorts, as well as &ldquo;needless ostentation.&rdquo; A strong streak of jealousy against the so-called &ldquo;breadbasket&rdquo; provinces of Reikland, Stirland, Averland, and the Moot rises up in drunken rages. More than ever, stout soldiers are toasting old glories with Kislev Vodka, sinking into drunken stupors or violent rampages. Short shrift is also given to those who complain of hardship.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Ostlanders, like most Imperials, honour all the gods and celebrate their feast days. If one god is favoured over another, however, it is Sigmar, who is worshipped with a degree of devotion not often seen north of the Empire. Surrounded by lands that lean toward Ulric, Taal and Rhya, few know why this is so, though many offer explanations. Devout Ostlanders say it stems from the time when, soon after the founding of the Empire, a great dragon ravaged Ostland. The other electors and their armies were afraid to face the beast, so Sigmar came alone and killed it after a great fight alongside the Ostland Count.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>On the other hand, cynics suggest that Ostlanders are so devoted because their &ldquo;poor cousin&rdquo; Electors have to keep borrowing money from wealthy Reiklanders and thus need to keep them happy. Whatever the truth, it is a fact that even the smallest Ostlander village sports multiple shrines to Sigmar. Ostlanders are known for the strange pacing and Kislevite tones of their speech. They frequently pause in the middle of a sentence. The Ostland accent is seldom imitated as it is associated with poverty.&nbsp;<strong>-Warhammer Forum</strong><sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.CcNJsS4jSwB6Ug1J]{Endurance}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.7pQo66cESWttzIlb]{Gamble}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.I0yPc4PH5erWJLmu]{Intimidate}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.EXysjCwmGzCOiRDx]{Language (Gospodarinyi)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Ungol)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Ostland)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.zZUX7wO4rOo8k9F0]{Navigation}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.os4NKy5Oy6sRt1eh]{Outdoor Survival}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZUldeWVqTnMRw5xD]{Sail (Cog)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.hodHqFNKAmu40ajh]{Swim}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fn8QNQQ1S2rh12Us]{Doomed}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>One&nbsp;@Table[talents], @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RmY0CUjiFYZ3GEKY]{Very Resilient}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.spdiWsONKTzkLbg3]{Stone Soup}, Three&nbsp;@Table[talents]</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"reikland\">7. Reikland</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The Reiklanders are the descendants of the fierce Unberogens, a warrior tribe of the northern Old World which saw the lands unified under their king Sigmar during the founding years of the Empire. At their best, Reiklanders are friendly, sociable, and open-minded, more so than the rest of the Empire.</p>\n<p>Reiklanders are optimists who believe that the best is yet to come. They point out several reasons for this: the natural bounty of their lands, an educated and energetic populace, and the fact that Sigmar was one of them. How could the future be dim for a land and people that once gave birth to a god? Reiklanders have adopted Sigmar's message of Imperial unity wholeheartedly.</p>\n<p>Reiklanders take a keen interest in the affairs of the other Imperial provinces, and often point out that \"something should be done\" when terrible fates befall their neighbours. Robust supporters of the Imperial military, many young Reikland nobles enter the army to make their name and fortune. Considered natural \"officer material\" the chances of advancement are considerably better for those of Reiklander birth, much to others' disapproval.</p>\n<p>Reiklanders almost always answer an Imperial call-to-arms in large numbers, and feel as if its their duty to come to the aid of less fortunate parts of the Empire. Indeed, among some Reiklanders the ideal of expansion is as strong as it was in the early days of the Empire: Agitators in Ubersreik and Altdorf press for war with Bretonnia to reclaim the \"West March.\"</p>\n<p>Merchants' guilds desire to see the Emperor strengthen his position against the Elector Counts, and thereby call for unitary trade laws, which would be overseen by Imperial officials, something the Electors fiercely resist, determined to see no further centralisation of Imperial political power.</p>\n<p>Fashion plays a more important role in a Reiklander's social life than in most other provinces. The peasantry, of course, care little for such fripperies, but amongst the growing middle classes the correct sleeves, shoes, and colours are matters of great import. The Reiklander nobility tend to set the fashion for a season, leaving it to the merchant and other \"grubby tradesmen\" to copy their new styles as fast as they can.</p>\n<p>The presence of the Imperial Court in Altdorf has only served to exacerbate these tendencies. Recent vogues have included Bretonnian styles, the \"new rustic,\" and most recently a return to simple militaristic clothing reminiscent of an earlier era. Slashed sleeves, elaborate codpieces, and reliquary charms remain as fashionable as ever.</p>\n<p>At their worst, Reiklanders are arrogant, overbearing, and drunken slaves to fashion. Notorious for their ability to celebrate at the drop of a hat, the image of the beribboned Reiklander sot is a popular stereotype amongst the rest of the Empire. In certain places the small black insects that plague an ill-kept taproom are known as \"Reikflies\" as they can detect the smallest amount of ale unerringly.</p>\n<p>The people of many of the other Imperial provinces are suspicious of the fashionable, cosmopolitan nature of the Reikland men, claiming that they are effeminate and womanish for caring so much about what they wear. Curiously, Reiklander men also have a reputation as wife-stealing, pig-buggering philanderers.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>More than one Talabeclander husband has found his woman seduced by the charming words and dashing look of a Reiklander dandy. Reiklander women, meanwhile, are known for their beauty, as well as unbearably vain personality.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Loud, outspoken, and often smug about the imagined superiority of their opinions, Reiklanders are traditionally known to be controlling and strongly opinionated. Their lack of stamina is also a welcome source for vituperative and malicious comments amongst the other peoples of the Empire. <sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Reiklander Characters use the default Human Creation rules from the <a title=\"WFRP4e Core Module\" href=\"https://foundryvtt.com/packages/wfrp4e-core/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">WFRP4e Core Module</a>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"stirland\">8. Stirland</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>For their part, the folk of Stirland are proud of their preservation of ancient customs, and of their &ldquo;long view&rdquo; of life. At their best, Stirlanders are calm, thoughtful, and practised at taking their time about things. Fond of long, ribald tales, the local tavern is the heart of any Stirlander community. Here people gather to hear their favourite stories, the local gossip, and occasionally news from the outside world. Racing is also a firm favourite of the Stirland people&mdash;though not the traditional foot or horseback racing liked by the rest of the Empire.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>As most communities are based about arable farmlands, geese, cows, pigs, and ratting dogs are frequently raced against one another in local competitions. Usually held on a festival or market day, the winning beast is often awarded &ldquo;ribbons and reprieve,&rdquo; meaning it will never be destined for the table. At their worst, Stirlanders are isolationist, suspicious, and highly conservative. Stirlanders, however, see themselves as simply keeping traditions: &ldquo;They&rsquo;ve worked in the past, so no sense in changing now,&rdquo; as Stirlanders like to say. They find it hard to make friends&mdash;often taking years to accept newcomers within their communities. Most of the Empire regards them as savages, simply for their custom of drinking hot ale.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>There are many other odd customs; for example, when strangers approach a village in the Stirh&uuml;gels, children will throw pig droppings at them in the belief that this will drive away evil spirits. They believe that a person hit with tossed pig excrement is especially protected. In the villages near Sylvania, houses and windows are lined with an especially pungent strain of local garlic to ward of what are euphemistically called &ldquo;the Count&rsquo;s Men.&rdquo; When someone vanishes, locals swear that the fault lies with old garlic, not that the folk belief itself is wrong. Stirlanders within the central territories of the province are known for their dislike of Halflings, for they still resent the 1500-year-old decision that tore away their best farmlands and gave them to &ldquo;the Shorties.&rdquo; Although this resentment rarely breaks out in violence, the belief that Halflings are thieves at heart is stronger here than in any other part of the Empire.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Forum</strong><sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.d3VZwO4Y5JH5DXdT]{Bribery}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.bSWoV1IiS5qWNw39]{Evaluate}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Cg2b92BRjvxYXZiE]{Language (Mootish)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oMaJZ5cvCJeOUq9H]{Leadership}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Stirland)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZQSm2AwrgT2cHG0C]{Ranged (Bow)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rvd0S8Z0v2m0MHmD]{Sleight of Hand}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Xk5tp3aasPNtk4zt]{Stealth (Rural)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.zkI6tIqbyAZvh0Th]{Stealth (Urban)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fn8QNQQ1S2rh12Us]{Doomed}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>One&nbsp;@Table[talents], @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.7bZjB82f6LSkeczP]{Nimble Fingered}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}, Three&nbsp;@Table[talents]</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"sylvania\">9. Sylvania</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Sylvanians often have a blas&eacute; attitude towards death and the dead that is at odds with their neighbours. They take a perverse pride in the harshness of their life, seeing others as &ldquo;soft&rdquo; for living in warmer climes, using blackpowder weapons, or associating with the other races. Sylvanians believe in the worst stereotypes, and it is common to find they believe Dwarfs drown cats, and Halflings routinely eat each other. This attitude goes all the way back to the Fennones of old, who refused to deal with the Dwarfs they encountered in the foothills of the Worlds Edge Mountains because they ignorantly believed that they came from the same place as the marauding Greenskins who raided their land.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>The largest towns of Sylvania are still considered rural backwaters by the standards of cultured Empire folk, half-empty places where everybody wears codpieces that haven't been fashionable for over fifty years. These towns support only a few burghers, as few can afford their bills, and most are merely overgrown villages that happen to be built on better land. Since Sylvania&rsquo;s population never truly recovered from the Black Plague and the contagions that followed, overcrowding had never been a problem.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>In addition to disease, mutation is rife amongst the peasants. The thin soil has been riddled with Warpstone since 1111 IC, giving Sylvania one of the highest rates of mutation in the Empire. The most deformed Mutants are cast out into the woods or sent to Drakenhof, but many who would be burned elsewhere are accepted in Sylvania. Hunchbacks, walleyes, and those with additional digits are treated no differently from others.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>With the low yield of crops, starvation is a constant threat, and most accept hunger pains as a normal part of life. Turning to &ldquo;sweet pork&rdquo;, the Sylvanians&rsquo; euphemism for Human flesh, is considered distasteful but not evil. Desperate times can call for desperate measures, and the Ghouls that raid the villages often lived amongst their victims the winter before.</p>\n<p><sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup>All this has led to the Sylvanians becoming an insular people. They harbour resentments towards the Empire, especially Stirland. They avoid all contact with the outside world, and many know embarrassingly little about it. It is not uncommon for Sylvanians to not realise they are a part of the Empire, and many could not name the current Emperor if asked. Those who do know a little of the lands beyond their own know that they will not be accepted there, and Empire folk have as low of an opinion of Sylvanians as Sylvanians do of the Empire folk.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong><sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.LGHozP5gmQ8cuDQV]{Athletics}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.4IGdIhnwTaZijzg7]{Charm Animal}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.CcNJsS4jSwB6Ug1J]{Endurance}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Sylvania)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Undead)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Vampires)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.PzimjNx9Ojq4g6mV]{Melee (Polearm)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.os4NKy5Oy6sRt1eh]{Outdoor Survival}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Xk5tp3aasPNtk4zt]{Stealth (Rural)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.JLzJws09GMw9GWBV]{Coolheaded}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.oQzTJEXUx28sCiH3]{Sharp}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.jrFIFLhyOYwcyMUl]{Flee!}, Three&nbsp;@Table[talents]</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"talabecland\">10. Talabecland</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>A thickly forested place, Talabecland has a reputation for barbarism and ignorance amongst the other Imperial Electoral Provinces. The folk of Talabecland ignore this nonsense, holding instead a private pride in their forestcraft and practical skills. At their best, Talabeclanders are patient woodsfolk, with a quiet intensity and honour. Reading, writing, and the scholastic arts are respected, but held in second place to the lore of the wilds.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>The men of Talabecland favour silence and deed over long speeches, but their womenfolk have a soft side for a honeyed word. As a consequence, rakish types, poets, and Reiklanders are viewed with firm suspicion throughout the province -- though in general Talabeclanders are more welcoming than their rural Stirlander cousins.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>The role of the father is considered especially important to the folk of the Great Woods. Even town-born men take their sons to the woods during the summer and teach them how to follow a trail, light a fire, and catch a meal. This is considered a matter of practicality, just like a Marienburger learning to swim. A lad without a father to patiently teach him the ways of the wood and the bow is considered unlucky.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Talabeclanders, even their nobility, are unusually self-effacing for an Imperial people. Their histories tell tales of great deeds while downplaying the role of the individual persons involved. &nbsp;At the tournaments held every two years at K&uuml;sel, Talabecland knights wear the provincial colours on their shields, the only indication of their families being a small badge on their shoulders.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Tradition considers the glory won to belong to the people of Talabecland as a whole.&nbsp;The Talabeclanders are also a religious people, revering all the gods of the Empire, but holding special reverence for Taal and Rhya. Indeed, Taal's greatest temple is found in the small woods outside Talabheim in the Great Crater.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Ulric is also popular, for although not braggarts, Talabeclanders are known for their warlike ways. Talabheim itself was the home of the Cult of Ulric for a while in the Second Millennium IC, when the Ar-Ulric left Middenheim for Talabheim after a dispute with the local elector count.</p>\n<p>At their worst, Talabeclanders can be argumentative, primitive, hard drinking, and just plain mean. And though they do not wear leaves, as outsiders sometimes accuse them of doing, Talabeclanders generally eschew elaborate clothes and prefer practical garb that can stand up to rough handling.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong><sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.4IGdIhnwTaZijzg7]{Charm Animal}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Talabecland)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.zZUX7wO4rOo8k9F0]{Navigation}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.os4NKy5Oy6sRt1eh]{Outdoor Survival}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Fs06sr7y9JKpVQmB]{Perception}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZQSm2AwrgT2cHG0C]{Ranged (Bow)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rt2rGSwFDCDHPh0A]{Track}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:</strong>&nbsp;@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fn8QNQQ1S2rh12Us]{Doomed} <em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.XIcDsaW4D8wScezw]{Accurate Shot}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.5lcttqGToT54WFrl]{Marksman}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.QsrXxGZiHjth7RMg]{Savvy}, Three&nbsp;@Table[talents]</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2 id=\"wissenland\">11. Wissenland</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The folk of Wissenland are known to be a dour lot. The fall of Solland was a dark chapter in Imperial history, and Wissenlanders seem to carry this shame with them. They are a hardy people, given to few words and little emotion. Their stony implacability is known to soften when they are in their cups, and on rare occasions they might break into &ldquo;The Lament of Solland&rdquo; or other such lonesome ballad. At their best, Wissenlanders are stoic, dependable, and willing to endure hardship should it be needful. At their worst, they are depressing, dull, and obsessed with the gods.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>For all their earthy practicality, Wissenlanders are religiously devout, their towns and villages hosting multiple shrines, chapels, and temples to all the recognised gods, as well as local spirits. Many Wissenlanders take a few minutes each day to visit a temple or shrine, working their way through the gods over the course of a week. The people of Wissenland claim this is simple devotion on their part, while cynics elsewhere cannot decide if they are show-offs or trying to cover all the angles&mdash;or both.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>While all the gods are honoured in Wissenland, Sigmar and Taal and Rhya have special prominence. Sigmar&rsquo;s cult centres in the west, where contact with the Dwarfs is greatest. Both Wissenburg and Meissen have large temples that host shrines for the Dwarfs to worship their own deities, whilst upriver from <a class=\"new\" title=\"Geschburg (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvR2VzY2hidXJnP2FjdGlvbj1lZGl0JnJlZGxpbms9MQ==\">Geschburg</a> in the foothills of the Grey Mountains lies the shrine of <a class=\"new\" title=\"Sigmar Protector (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvU2lnbWFyX1Byb3RlY3Rvcj9hY3Rpb249ZWRpdCZyZWRsaW5rPTE=\">Sigmar Protector</a>, a popular pilgrimage spot. It was here in the 14th century that a force of the Elector Count was trapped by marauding Orcs. Their destruction looked certain.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong><sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.CcNJsS4jSwB6Ug1J]{Endurance}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.cYtU0ORRFCOpQLWz]{Intuition}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.5EvSIh1khpt77uM7]{Language (Bretonnian)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Emd8lVdIpaXTxLwL]{Language (Estalian)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.12e3H6NX4JH0bwI3]{Language (Tilean)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oMaJZ5cvCJeOUq9H]{Leadership}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Wissenland)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.H2upcZ7q7qAPtPic]{Ranged (Blackpowder)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.wKwel9MG7NIG3i3w]{Trade (Miner)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.wKwel9MG7NIG3i3w]{Trade (Farmer)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fn8QNQQ1S2rh12Us]{Doomed}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.JLzJws09GMw9GWBV]{Coolheaded}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.QsrXxGZiHjth7RMg]{Savvy}, Three&nbsp;@Table[talents]</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.KRlyg1RMCYw4NXtP"}}}
{"_id":"QmSUiNGDtqxjnGf9","name":"Medals & Honors of the Empire","content":"<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Medals &amp; Honors of the Empire</h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Each Province of the Empire has its own, unique military traditions and structure, its own battlefield conditions and foes to fight. To reflect this, each Province has their own customs, ceremonies and awards for the men and women who serve the Empire from Soldiers and Cavalrymen, to Witch Hunters, or even Knights of particular skill, heroism, or stubborn tenacity. Man&rsquo;s allies are not exempt from these honors, as many a Dwarf, Elf, Halfling and even Ogre have received their fair share of accommodations and celebrations for their service. From the noblest of Elven Sorcerer or Dwarfen Engineer to the rowdiest of Tilean Mercenaries or Ogre Maneaters, the Empire has made sure to award its most faithful allies.</p>\n<p>Included below are those commendations unique to the Empire. These medals and honors are a tradition within the Empire&rsquo;s legacy dating back centuries and represent meritorious service against the main foes of the Mankind: The mutants that infest the forests and underbellies of all Empire towns and villages, the Orc hordes invading from the South in the Badlands, the Dark Elf corsairs and Norscan Marauders raiding from the Sea of Claws, those Chaos Warbands from the North that call the Chaos Wastes their home, and the Beastmen Warherds active in the Drakwald Forest. These are but a few of the innumerable threats that the Empire must face every day and have done so for over 2500 years.</p>\n<p>Additionally, there are informal awards, marks of reputation rather than formal commendation, given by Imperial command. These honors are often recognized by a given Empire officer, knight or noble lord to acknowledge a warrior&rsquo;s skill and history fighting one of Mankind&rsquo;s many foes.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>I - Kill Counts, War Trophies &amp; Titles</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<h3>Hunter</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Killer</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Reaper</h3>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>II - Imperial Honors</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<h3>Artillerist's Honors</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Black Raven</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Bronze Stag</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Golden Eagle</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Iron Comet</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Magnus Cross</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Martyr's Medal</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Medal of Destiny</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Meteoric Medal</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Platinum Owl</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Pure Soul Medal</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Rat Slayer Commendation</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Sacred Fire Medal</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Silver Wolf</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>White Dove</h3>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>I - Kill Counts, War Trophies &amp; Titles</h2>\n<p>For many warriors, each victory is accompanied by a simple ritual: a notch on a weapon or piece of armor, or a trophy from a fallen foe, a count for every enemy killed in service to the Empire. These simple counts add up over time, to eventually become a full-fledged part of the warrior&rsquo;s identity, fully incorporated in their heraldry and status. As a warrior moves through the ranks, their reputations as a fearsome fighter of a given enemy grows, eventually adding to their legendary reputation on the battlefield.</p>\n<p>These counts are collectively known as Kill Counts. Kill Counts are an informal honor, which means they hold no physical indication of accomplishments unlike medals, with the exception of trophies. Kill Counts in the form of trophies can be anything from a foe&rsquo;s weapon, armor, trinket or even their skull and other various body parts. Kill Counts are a part of the reputation of the warrior and are more a measure of their respect and status among knights, priests and soldiers, both within the Empire and among its enemies, than an adornment for a uniform.</p>\n<p>Kill Counts are a form of recognition for victory in battles, for causing damage and destruction to the goals and forces of a given adversary of the Empire. As such, Kill Counts are generally recognized after a certain number of successful battles or quests against a given foe. Optionally, the GM may wish to keep a running tally of every confirmed kill made by the warrior and have Kill Counts be a true count of the death toll the warrior has inflicted on the forces arrayed against the Empire of Mankind.</p>\n<p>Kill Counts are always applied to a particular enemy of the Empire. The types of Enemies represented by Kill Counts have to do with the creature, species or nation of the enemy type. Each of the major types of enemies and adversaries active within the Empire is an acceptable type of antagonist to be recognized by Kill Counts, which is normally a group of people or creatures, such as &lsquo;Rebels&rsquo;, &lsquo;Beastmen&rsquo;, &lsquo;Orcs&rsquo;, or &lsquo;Outlaws&rsquo;.</p>\n<p>Everyone records their Kill Counts differently. Counts may be written down in journals, painted onto a shield, notched into weapons, represented with elaborate body scars or tattoos, or displayed as a myriad of trophies hanging from banners, mounts, or armor.</p>\n<p>Each type of Kill Count gives the warrior bonuses for fighting their adversaries, and additionally marks the warrior as an implacable foe of one of the Empire&rsquo;s many hated enemies.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>1. Hunter</h3>\n<p>The warrior has become recognized and adept at rooting out a particular adversary of the Empire. Over the course of their adventures, the warrior has learned to recognize the telltale signs of one of the Empire&rsquo;s enemies and can recognize common battle tactics, tracks and other signs of their presence in the area.</p>\n<p>The warrior has likely developed a reputation throughout their current area as a skilled combatant against a given foe. They will often be given a nickname based off the foe they face: &ldquo;Orc Seeker,&rdquo; &ldquo;Gor Hunter,&rdquo; or &ldquo;Bandit Catcher,&rdquo; for only a few examples. The GM and player are encouraged to come up with an appropriate appellation for any warrior that receives this status, based on their career and the specifics of their exploits.</p>\n<p><strong>Requirements:</strong> The warrior has been blooded against a particular enemy of the Empire, with a few successful encounters against that adversary under their belt. Optionally, the GM might wish to keep a full tally of the enemies they have killed. If this is the case, this Kill Count is awarded for 50 or more confirmed kills of a given enemy of the Empire by the character.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> You are well versed in discerning the movements, trails and patterns for the given enemy. You gain a <strong>+10 bonus to Perception and Psychology Tests</strong> related to the specific enemy on your travels (such as Tests to track them and Tests to avoid Surprise or Fear in combat).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>2. Killer</h3>\n<p>The warrior has slain many of a given foe, and the locals in power have taken notice. Just as with other Kill Counts, the warrior is likely to have gained a reputation. The character is likely known throughout its current area with a nickname like &ldquo;Wrecker Killer&rdquo; or &ldquo;Zombie Butcher.&rdquo;</p>\n<p><strong>Requirements:</strong>&nbsp;The warrior has been an implacable foe of this enemy. Award this honor for successfully completing two or more adventures against a given adversary. Optionally, the GM can award the character this honor for 100 or more confirmed kills of a given enemy by the warrior.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> You have experienced first-hand the behaviors and tactics of your foe and can now begin to predict their behaviors and exploit their idiosyncrasies. You gain a <strong>+10 to any Intelligence Tests</strong> having to do with the chosen enemy, including and especially Lore Tests. Additionally, you are extremely adept at combating your specific enemy and gain a bonus of +1 SL on all combat Tests against the specified threat.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>3. Reaper</h3>\n<p>The warrior has developed a reputation throughout the Province, or even the Empire, as an expert fighter against a certain threat, and might be treated to such hushed sobriquets as &ldquo;Goblin Slayer,&rdquo; &ldquo;Chaos Render,&rdquo; &ldquo;Morr&rsquo;s Right Hand,&rdquo; or &ldquo;Sigmar&rsquo;s Justice.&rdquo; More likely than not, the character and their party has also developed a reputation with the enemy themselves, and might even be picked out for ambushes, targeted for assassination, or face other such reactive measures whenever their presence becomes known to their foes.</p>\n<p><strong>Requirements:</strong> The warrior has slaughtered scores of enemies of the Empire. Award this Kill Count for having successfully completed five or more adventures against a particular foe. Optionally, the GM can award this Kill Count if the character has decimated the enemy forces in numerous engagements, likely over the course of years or decades, and has earned 300 or more confirmed kills against this foe.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> You have faced this enemy in innumerable battles, and your combat prowess against this foe has become legendary. You know exactly how the enemy behaves, and how and where to hit that enemy when it is weakest. You inflict a bonus +1 Damage when attacking the chosen enemy and the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.8pVzgPkgWpTJvfhG]{Fearless (Enemy Type)} Talent is added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>Additionally, the enemy has learned to fear you and the tales around you. You gain a +10 to Intimidation Tests and the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.traits.pTorrE0l3VybAbtn]{Fear (1)} Trait against any enemy who is aware of your fearsome reputation. For every +100 additional confirmed kills of the specific enemy your @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.traits.pTorrE0l3VybAbtn]{Fear} Rank increases by 1. If you have been particularly effective at routing, slaying and disrupting the plans of a specific faction within the many enemy races of Order (such as a Chaos cult, Skaven clan or a particular tribe of Greenskins or Beastmen), the GM might wish to give those enemies the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.psychologies.5hH73j2NgPdsLCZN]{Hatred} Psychology against you to properly reflect their sworn vendettas and oaths of vengeance.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>II - Imperial Honors</h2>\n<p>Imperial Honors are gallantry medals awarded by the lords and ladies within the various Provinces for service to the Empire &ldquo;fighting in the name of the emperor and Sigmar himself.&rdquo; Considering how much leaders often expect out of the average soldier or citizen, receipt of one of these honors is a rare moment, indeed. These medals are considered very important, and their titles are long-winded. For example, the full title of the Iron Comet would be, &ldquo;For Distinguished Service, Against the Enemies of Mankind and the God of the Empire, Iron Comet Medal.&rdquo; Imperial Honors are usually very large and ostentatious, though there is considerable variance in this regard. Receipt of these medals does not go unnoticed by the soldiery, priesthoods, knightly orders or nobility. Imperial Honors are always awarded for specific feats of bravery and skill; each one is often accompanied by a scar and a story. The average man or dwarf warrior will often ask the bearers to recount their tales of bygone battles, partly out of curiosity and a sense of camaraderie, but also in the hopes that they might pick up a few helpful pointers along the way.</p>\n<p><strong>Medal Notes: </strong>Talents given by medals only apply to the initial receiver of the medal and non-Talent bonuses cannot be obtained by those who have not earned the medal themselves, however the medal must still be worn by the initial receiver. All medals can be identified with an<strong> Easy (+40) Skill Test</strong> using @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Empire)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Heraldry)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (History)}, or other similar Skills. Characters with Careers in the <em>Courtier </em>and <em>Warrior</em> Class may roll an <strong>Average (+20) Intelligence</strong> Test to know if they recognize any medal. Fake medals can be detected with an @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.bSWoV1IiS5qWNw39]{Evaluate} Test by anyone with the Numismatics Talent with the difficulty determined by the GM. The punishment of being caught using a fake medal is different within each Province but is often life imprisonment, forced service in the local army or militia, or simply death.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>1. Artillerist&rsquo;s Honors</h3>\n<p>The Artillerist&rsquo;s Honors is given to those heroes of the Empire who have decimated their way through enemy lines and into the true heart of invading armies from a distance with the expert use of artillery pieces&mdash;ballistae, cannons, etc. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from the engineers, artillerists and soldiers of the Empire, as soldiers are the most affected by frontline warfare preferring to deal with as few combatants as possible, while engineers and artillery crews are quick to impress with well-placed, calculated shots and good use of their siege equipment.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> A gold medallion with the image of a cannon etched on top.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong> 200 Confirmed kills using siege weapons and the destruction of a Chaos Dwarf, Ogre or Skaven engine of war.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> +10 to Lore Tests related to Armory, Construction, Engineering and Explosives, and the wearer gains a bonus of +10 to @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.2Y91ebFapH6zRfHk]{Ranged (Engineering)} Tests when using siege equipment.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>2. Black Raven</h3>\n<p>The Black Raven is given to those heroes of the Empire who have vanquished massive amounts of Undead abominations and helped stem the tide of rotten flesh by destroying their vampire and necromancer masters. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from Morrians, who cherish the preservation and respect for the dead above all else&mdash;with necromancy being the worst means of desecration.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong>&nbsp;A silver medallion inlaid with black gemstone and the image of a raven etched in with a skull in its center.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong>&nbsp;Slaying at least 200 Undead and at least one powerful Undead warrior, such as a Blood Knight, Ghoul King, Necromancer, or Vampire Noble.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong>&nbsp;The wearer of this medal&rsquo;s melee attacks against Undead gain the Damaging Weapon Quality, and the wearer gains a bonus of +10 to all Psychology Tests related to Undead. If the melee weapon already has Damaging it is replaced with the Impact Quality instead when striking Undead. If you do not have the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.JLzJws09GMw9GWBV]{Coolheaded} Talent already, it will be added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>3. Bronze Stag</h3>\n<p>The Bronze Stag is given to those heroes of the Empire who have hunted down and slain a great monstrous beast and protected the people from its ravenous wrath using Taal&rsquo;s favored method, the bow. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from Taal&rsquo;s followers and any huntsmen regardless of the god they serve.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> A bronze medallion with the image of a stag etched on top.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong> Slaying a mighty @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.traits.8slW8CJ2oVTxeQ6q]{Size (Monstrous)} creature by yourself using only a bow.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> The wearer of this medal&rsquo;s ranged bow attacks against Animals and Monsters gain the Damaging Weapon Quality. If the bow already has Damaging it is replaced with the Impact Quality instead. If you do not have the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.5lcttqGToT54WFrl]{Marksman} Talent already, it will be added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>4. Golden Eagle</h3>\n<p>The Golden Eagle is given to those heroes of the Empire who have displayed and proven their unmatched tactical and military knowledge on the battlefield. In the face of overwhelming opposition on all sides, the Empire cannot afford the same losses in war as their enemies from Greenkins to the Undead, who can replenish quickly. It takes a strong tactical mind to earn a place in high command and even more so to maintain their office. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from Myrmidians, military officers and high-ranking Imperial officials.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong>&nbsp;A gold medallion with a silver trim and the image of an eagle clutching a spear with its talons etched on top.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong>&nbsp;An extreme act of tactical or military brilliance on the battlefield that either allows for a major victory against a vastly superior foe (numbers, war gear, champions, etc.) with minimal to no losses or greatly turns the tide of battle from defeat to victory.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong>&nbsp;+10 to all @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore} Tests related to Warfare, and the wearer of this medal&rsquo;s melee attacks using a polearm gain the Precise Weapon Quality. If you do not have the Sharp Talent already, it will be added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>5. Iron Comet</h3>\n<p>This Iron Comet is awarded for spearheading an act of Sigmar&rsquo;s will to end a threat to the Empire by cutting off the heads of their leaders&mdash;archenemies well known to the God of the Empire, predominantly servants of Chaos, Greenskins and Undead. These champions and warlords are heavily relied upon by their warbands, cults or clans, and their loss is a devastating blow to the enemy. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from Sigmarites regardless of social status, from nobles and priests, to the common folk and peasants of the Empire devoted to Sigmar.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> An iron medallion with the image of the Twin Tailed Comet etched on top and a red gemstone inserted in its center.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong> Slaying a powerful and dangerous Daemon, Greenskin or Undead champion such as a Daemon Lord of Chaos, Greenskin Warboss, Master Necromancer or Vampire Lord in melee combat.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> The medal wearer&rsquo;s melee attacks against Daemons, Greenskins and Undead gain the Damaging Weapon Quality. Any warhammers (the signature weapon of Sigmar) or swords you wield gain +1 Damage with this medal equipped. If you do not have either the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born} or @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Zf0vk2rjllpDh0Ua]{Very Strong} Talent already, one may be added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>6. Magnus Cross</h3>\n<p>The Magnus Cross is the most famous and widely recognized medal in the Empire. It was first issued during the reign of Magnus the Pious under its original name as the &ldquo;Imperial Cross&rdquo; but has since been renamed in his honor since the great emperor&rsquo;s death. It was originally awarded to Magnus&rsquo; personal honor guard during the Great War Against Chaos and has been used ever since to reward those who would lay down their lives to protect the Empire&rsquo;s greatest leaders from the innumerable threats they face daily. A character with this medal can expect the highest amount of respect from the vast majority of Imperial citizens, nobles and military officials across the Empire, regardless of social status.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong>&nbsp;A black cross made of obsidian gemstone, with a gold trim and a golden skull wearing a civic crown in its center.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong>&nbsp;Preserving the Empire by protecting an Imperial figure of great importance from harm, such as an Elector Count or the Emperor (with their knowledge of your actions, of course).</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong>&nbsp;Whenever the wearer of this medal inflicts a Critical Hit against a Greenskin, Servant of Chaos or Undead, you may roll twice on the Critical Wounds Table and pick the higher result. Greenskins, Servants of Chaos and Undead may not ignore the Critical Wound under any circumstances (unless they successfully dodge it with an Opposed @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.1jCxbFAUuFuAPLJl]{Dodge} Test), including spending a Fate Point, using Critical Deflection or having the Impenetrable Armor Quality. The @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.vMYEkrWj0ip6ZOdv]{Resistance (Corruption)} Talent is added to the Talent list of any career you are in, and any bonus effects for Tests you gain from your Status are doubled with any Imperials who respect Status.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>7. Martyr&rsquo;s Medal</h3>\n<p>This medal is awarded to the grizzled and scarred veterans of the Empire, from the common swordsman to the militiamen and mercenaries that aid their local Provinces in their time of need, and payed the price for it. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from the militia locals, mercenaries, soldiers and law enforcement of the Empire, retired or active in their duties.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> A bronze medallion with silver filigree and the image of a cracked skull etched on top.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong> An act of true bravery and sacrifice in the name of the Empire in the face of overwhelming odds and certain death to protect its people, so great it results in the loss of limbs or causes permanent mental scaring. Acts may include defending a village from an onslaught of Beastmen that overwhelm the defenders three to one, or a raid on an Orc encampment to break the back of a possible Orc invasion on a nearby town just to name a few examples.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> Whenever the wearer of this medal is required to make a @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.psychologies.Ib2YQYChktDFN93y]{Fear} or @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.psychologies.meMkLEwdJIDLxM0B]{Terror} Test, they may spend a Fortune Point to automatically pass that Test with +Willpower Bonus SL and the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.8pVzgPkgWpTJvfhG]{Fearless (Any)} Talent is added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>8. Medal of Destiny</h3>\n<p>The Medal of Destiny is awarded is awarded for completing perilous deeds in the name of the Empire&rsquo;s most trusted and loyal subjects. Formed during the days of Magnus the Pious, the Medal of Destiny was created to reward only the most dedicated and loyal within the Empire&rsquo;s citizenry. Those who accept the near impossible tasks given are awarded with not only the medal and undying gratitude of the Province&rsquo;s officials, but a guaranteed promise of citizenship within the Empire and immediate elevation to noble status, the only medal of its kind to grant such. Due to its high value thanks to its promises of citizenship and noble status, it was decided that only the most carefully selected and tested noble officials within the Empire should be capable of awarding this medal to back up its legitimacy and avoid a complicated criminal element. These medals are forged by smiths from the Gold Order and as such are commonly tested by local Metal Wizards to be verified, in case a conman tries to act cheeky and flaunt their non-existent accomplishments and bogus status.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong>&nbsp;A gold medallion encrusted with gemstones in the colors of the local Province and the seal of a noble house etched on top.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong>&nbsp;Accomplishing perilous and borderline suicidal missions granted by an official of high esteem within the Empire, so dangerous you would have most likely needed divine aid to have survived.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong>&nbsp;The wearer of this medal gains 1 AP on the Body, and the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.u0CFf3xwiyidD9T5]{Luck} and @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.1IVGksL10N7GVrw3]{Noble Blood} Talents are added to the Talent list of any career you are in. If the AP is Damaged, it takes until sunrise the following day for it to recover.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>9. Meteoric Medal</h3>\n<p>The Meteoric Medal is an ancient&mdash;possibly the oldest&mdash;honor ever given from Dwarf to Mankind since the foundation of the Empire. Only the greatest allies to the Dwarf Clans and their lords are even considered for this honor, which is less a medal and more a runic artifact crafted with the insignia of the clan who forges it. This honor proves to the Dwarfs one who is worthy of their respect, regardless of their beard length. No Dwarf would dare speak ill of anyone showing this medal in their presence and would sooner take the Slayer Oath than disrespect one who has aided the Dwarfs so honorably in these dark times.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> A gromril medallion carved into the head of Grungni, the Dwarf god of artistry, metalwork and mining, and emblazoned with a clan insignia and a glowing rune on the back side of the medal.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong> Preserving the ancient oath of friendship between Man and Dwarf, or proving yourself an ally to their cause through other means, by committing an act of great heroism in their name, such as: aiding them in discovering and reclaiming a long lost dwarf hold, returning ancient sacred Dwarfen artifacts, or crossing off the name of one of the Dwarf&rsquo;s greatest enemies from the Great Book of Grudges itself.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> The wearer of this medal gains a @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.traits.Bvd2aZ0gQUXHfCTh]{Ward (9+)} Creature Trait against all attacks and spells targeting you. Each hit successfully saved increases the Ward&rsquo;s effectiveness by 1, to a maximum of @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.traits.Bvd2aZ0gQUXHfCTh]{Ward (6+)}. The Ward resets back to 9+ at the end of an encounter or if the medal is removed.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>10. Platinum Owl</h3>\n<p>The Platinum Owl is given to those heroes of the Empire who have dispatched justice so effectively within the Empire as to root out corruption and purge major internal struggles ripping apart the Empire from within. Be it in a court room, a dueling arena or through thorough investigation and espionage, those who expose and expunge the malign influences that threaten the political structure of the Empire are more than worthy of this medal. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from Verena&rsquo;s followers and law officials like judges, lawyers, scholars, bailiffs, watchmen, road wardens and even some witch hunters.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong>&nbsp;A platinum medallion carved in the shape of an owl&rsquo;s head with a golden sword and scale in its center.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong>&nbsp;A wise act of justice that roots out and destroys the corruption eating away at the Empire by reporting, exposing and possibly executing a corrupt individual of great social and political status.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong>&nbsp;+10 to @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore} Tests related to History, Law, Politics and Theology. If you do not have the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.QsrXxGZiHjth7RMg]{Savvy} Talent already, it will be added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>11. Pure Soul Medal</h3>\n<p>The Pure Soul Medal is given to the most pious and favored of the gods commonly worshipped within the Empire, from Patron Gods like Sigmar to the Classical Gods of the North and South from Ulric to Myrmidia. This medal is of such importance it is only awarded by Arch Lectors to the most righteous and dogmatic of religious fanatics within the Empire&mdash;not so fanatical as to be suicidal like the flagellants mind you, but equally as spirited and financially viable to their local temple. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from the followers of their dominant religion and all priests and cultists, regardless of their faith, so long as their followers don&rsquo;t hold a rivalry or animosity towards one another, similar to Ulricians and Sigmarites.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> A gold medallion, inlaid with iron and the image of a hammer etched in, with a silver skull in the hammer&rsquo;s head.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong> An act of extreme piety, one that proves unmistakably you are a fervent and loyal follower of your deity in the eyes your god and their servants. Recovering long lost religious artifacts, successfully launching a crusade against enemies of a given deity or going on a years-long spiritual journey across the Old World, aiding as many temples as possible enough for word to reach the Arch Lectures of the various faiths.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> +10 to @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.9xR9uO8FIvi4YsJp]{Pray} Tests and the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.wNvPXAhlKABl6hpk]{Pure Soul} Talent is added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>12. Rat Slayer Commendation</h3>\n<p>The Rat Slayer Commendation is unofficially known in private circles within the Imperial military and upper nobility as the &ldquo;Skaven Slayer Commendation.&rdquo; This medal is awarded to brave souls who risk their lives fighting the nefarious ratmen, without the luxuries of decent compensation or gratitude that benefit butchering better known threats to the Empire. This medal was created in honor of Mandred von Zelt, also known as Mandred Skavenslayer, one of the greatest Emperors in the Empire&rsquo;s history who pulled humanity out of the Black Death in the 12th Century IC, and a powerful champion of Ulric who devastated the Skaven in the ensuing wars against them. Most of the population will not recognize this emblem without prior knowledge of the Skaven, as is the intention of its design to keep attention towards it low. It will often be looked upon as a cheap, ugly piece of jewelry. However, within the right groups amongst the Imperial elite and revealing the heraldry of House Zelt on its back, many will acknowledge the medal wearer as a venerated champion of the Empire, but none will mention the word &ldquo;Skaven&rdquo; without caution.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> An iron medallion, inlaid with bronze with the image of a rat&rsquo;s head with two &lsquo;X&rsquo; marks over its eyes, and the heraldry of House Zelt emblazoned onto the back of the medal.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong> Slaying at least 200 Skaven and a powerful Skaven champion, such as a Grey Seer Lord, Master Assassin, Master Moulder, Warlock Chief Engineer or Warlord.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> The wearer of this medal&rsquo;s melee attacks against Rats and Skaven gain the Damaging Weapon Quality, and the wearer gains a bonus of +10 to all Psychology Tests related to Rats and Skaven. If the melee weapon already has Damaging it is replaced with the Impact Quality instead when striking Skaven.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>13. Sacred Fire Medal</h3>\n<p>The Sacred Fire Medal is awarded for eliminating a shadowy insurgent cell responsible for death, dissent and turmoil within the Empire. Things like secret Chaos cults, ambitious revolutionaries and hidden clans of nefarious ratmen are the fuel that keep the fires of Chaos expanding. Without these secretive, malevolent threats plaguing, killing and corrupting the people from within their communities, the growth of Chaos influence staggers or secedes.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong>&nbsp;A gold medallion encrusted with red gemstones and emblazoned with a red gem encrusted skull surrounded by flames.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong>&nbsp;Purging one of the Empire&rsquo;s large towns or cities by wiping out an entire underground network of its enemies, such as a Chaos Cult, Rebel Cell or a lesser Skaven Clan.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong>&nbsp;Wearers of this medal regain +1 Wound per hour and the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.xx8SgdWYEjKct7ym]{Implacable} Talent is added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>14. Silver Wolf</h3>\n<p>This Imperial Honor is awarded for spearheading an act of Ulric&rsquo;s will by challenging and cutting off the head of a powerful champion deemed worthy by the followers of the White Wolf. Archenemies well known to the temples of Ulric and Middenland consist of Beastmen, Greenskins and Mutants. These champions, warlords and cult leaders are heavily relied upon by their warbands, cults or clans, and their loss is a devastating blow to the enemy. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from Ulricians regardless of social status, from nobles and priests, to the common folk and peasants of the Empire devoted to Ulric.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> A silver medallion carved in the shape of a wolf&rsquo;s head with its features etched in.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong> Slaying a powerful and dangerous Beastman, Greenskin or Mutant champion such as a Beastlord, Chaos Cult Leader, or Greenskin Warboss in melee combat.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong> The medal wearer&rsquo;s melee attacks against Beastmen, Greenskins and Mutants, gain the Damaging Weapon Quality. Any warhammers or axes (the signature weapons of Ulric) you wield gain +1 Damage with this medal equipped. If you do not have either the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born} or @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RmY0CUjiFYZ3GEKY]{Very Resilient} Talent already, one may be added to the Talent list of any career you are in.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>15. White Dove</h3>\n<p>The White Dove is given to those heroes of the Empire who have prioritized the preservation and safety of life over merely taking it in battle. It takes more than firepower and strategic planning to win wars, and nothing is more valuable in conflict than the health of the soldiers and citizens fighting in them every day. Be it through curing crippling wounds, plague or combat fatigue, those who spend their days saving the lives of the Empire&rsquo;s people are more than deserving of this medal. A character showing this medal can expect respect and appreciation from Shallya&rsquo;s followers and healers such as medics, physicians, jade wizards and apothecaries.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong>&nbsp;A silver medallion inlaid with white gemstone and the image of a dove etched in with a blood drop in its center.</p>\n<p><strong>Awarded For:</strong>&nbsp;Purity and altruism that saves the lives of at least 100 people through acts of physical, emotional or spiritual healing.</p>\n<p><strong>Bonuses:</strong>&nbsp;+10 to @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.HXZaV1CJhmTvcAz4]{Heal} Tests and the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fEFAMNqh8nJIfBkM]{Field Dressing} Talent is added to the Talent list of any career you are in. If you have the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fEFAMNqh8nJIfBkM]{Field Dressing} Talent already, the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.NP4EHyyh1yOLbsPU]{Surgery} Talent is added instead.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.Td0ZQLv4dNwFrJT2"}}}
{"_id":"ZQblwfUY6YGyqIH3","name":"Regiments of Renown","content":"<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Regiments of Renown</h1>\n<p>While most Empire troops wear their provincial or city-state colors, there are notable exceptions that do not follow this tradition. Some regiments have performed legendry feats on past battlefields that are forever commemorated by a symbolic change of uniform design or color. Other unorthodox formations adopt the style of a maverick leader or develop their own heritage over the course of long campaigning. Age-old enemies, unique fighting tactics, or even a chance to embellish their own mythic reputation have all been reason enough for regiments to adopt non-standard colors and symbols.</p>\n<p>At your third Career level, some provinces gain the option for you to enlist in a special Regiment based on your skill, performance or reputation on the battlefield, and possibly your Province of origin, providing you an additional Talent to purchase and a unique trapping upon enlistment. However, your Career 3 rank is reverted to @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FgVH1pPS9oRq0o2Z]{Soldier}, as you are abandoning a potential promotion as a @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.8vPHNztfk9x7K2Na]{Sergeant} to join a more elite unit, but your Social Status for Career 3 remains the same. You will still have access to all Skills and Talents available at Career 3 and 4, including the Regiment Skills and Talents from your home province, but you gain none of the Trappings received at Career 3 and you still receive orders on the same level as a Career 2 Soldier. You will regain your authority once you progress to Career 4 as an Officer, and all Trappings as listed are granted as normal.</p>\n<p>Some special Regiments only recruit locally, while others recruit anyone who has proven themselves in a way sufficient enough to be worthy of enlisting. It is the GM&rsquo;s discretion as to who, why and how the PC is allowed to join.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Aldtorf Company of Honor</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Carroburg Great Swords</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Death Jacks</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Fireloques of Ferlangen</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Gr&uuml;ndel's Defenders</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Helhunten's Redeemers</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Seahawks</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Sterntower Marksmen</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>The Death's Heads</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>The Swords of Ulric</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Van Klumpf's Buccaneers</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Von Kragsburg Guard</strong></h3>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\n<h2>1. Altdorf Company of Honor</h2>\n<p>The Altdorf Company of Honour, also known as the <em>Sons of the Reik</em>, are a Reikland regiment of highly-trained and highly-equipped troops dedicated to the service of the Emperor and the city of Altdorf.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>This highly distinguished regiment recruits exclusively from other Altdorf regiments, picking only the best and bravest men out of the many units that garrison the city in order to keep up with their fearsome reputation as an elite fighting force.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Other soldiers instantly recognise the regiment thanks to their distinctive appearance of yellow plumes and black steel armour, with their battlefield history soaked in tales of glory and victory. Traditionally led by the youngest son of one of the city's noble houses, the current Captain of this regiment is Otto Helstein, a valiant warrior eager to make his mark upon this world. Every Altdorf native knows the distinctive trumpet blast that announces when the regiment leaves the city gates for a distant campaign, and all of them offer praises to Sigmar to ensure the safe return of Altdorf's most favoured sons.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Altdorf/Reikland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Reiksplate Cuirass, Yellow Plumed Helm</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.x8g3U68oi8XzWiYr]{Commanding Presence} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Red and Blue</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>2. Carroburg Great Swords</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"Among the Empire's most-storied regiments, the Carroburg Greatswords have earned their bloody reputation by slaying all comers in defence of their home city.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The fame of the Carroburg Greatswords dates back to the Age of Three Emperors. In 1865 IC, they successfully defended the city of Carroburg, then under the control of Reikland, from the count of Middenland. Throughout the course of the battle, their white uniforms were stained red with blood. Since then, they have worn crimson uniforms in remembrance of that day.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Today, they fight in the service of Reikland, despite the fact that Carroburg has been reclaimed by Middenland. All but unbreakable in combat, \"Wade through blood and spill a bath-full more\" is the code by which the legendary Carroburg Greatswords live and die.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Middenland/Reikland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Carroburg Greatsword</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.NDetl9BhAQBVnHKf]{Combat Master} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Red and Silver</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>3. Death Jacks</h2>\n<p>The Death Jacks are renowed archers who can track a foe at speed through any forest. First recorded on the Wurtbad roll of honor in the year 2004, the Deathjacks were hired to scout ahead of the main Stirland army during the civil war between the Three Emperors. The Deathjacks have continued to be of service to the Empire, ambushing opposing scouts and finding hidden paths from which to take the foe unaware.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Used to fending for themselves, the Deathjacks have been dubbed the <em>Mutton-sticker</em> or <em>Thievingjacks</em> by their own comrades, as baggage trains and supplies mysteriously go missing in their presence. All is forgiven, when the archers return from a scouting mission, waving their banner to signify enemies ahead, or blaring the all-clear on their hunting horns.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Stirland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Death Jack Bow</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.jLJzZb4keVvE0qRv]{Deadeye Shot} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Green, Yellow and Red</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>4. Fireloques of Ferlangen</h2>\n<p>The Fireloques of Ferlagen are a troop of deadly accurate handgunners that have fought throughout the Province of Ostland, often under the army banner of Elector Count von Raukov himself. Wearing the black and white of their home province, the Fireloques of Ferlagen bear no formal insignia, but superstitiously decorate their hats and uniforms with the bones of fallen comrades and other good luck charms.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Even amongst the stubborn Ostlanders, the Fireloques of Ferlagen have gained a reputation for tenacity, holding their gun line and unleashing volley after volley of fire into approaching enemies. Their refusal to surrender the flank against marauders of the north during the three-day <a class=\"new\" title=\"Battle of Littered Bones (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvQmF0dGxlX29mX0xpdHRlcmVkX0JvbmVzP2FjdGlvbj1lZGl0JnJlZGxpbms9MQ==\"><em>Battle of Littered Bones</em></a> earned them the nickname of <em>Skull Clubbers</em>, as without gunpowder for the entire last day, they resorted to using their beloved handguns as blunt weapons to stem the tide of the attackers.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Ostland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Bone Charms, Quality Handgun</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.XIcDsaW4D8wScezw]{Accurate Shot} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Black and White</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>5. Gr&uuml;ndel's Defenders</h2>\n<p>Grundel's Defenders was first raised after the disastrous battle of the year 2421 IC when Goblin Warlord, Grom the Paunch of the Misty Mountains led an invasion through Black Fire Pass and savagely ransacked Nuln before sweeping through the heartlands of the Empire. Better coordination was needed between artillery and infantry, and in the wake of the devastation, new regiments were formed into battalions that trained and fought together.</p>\n<p>Baron <a class=\"new\" title=\"Albrecht Grudel (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvQWxicmVjaHRfR3J1ZGVsP2FjdGlvbj1lZGl0JnJlZGxpbms9MQ==\">Albrecht Grudel</a> first named and equipped those under his command and his sons have continued the tradition to this day. Tasked with protecting the batteries of cannons and mortar from the enemy, Grundel's Defenders have never failed in their honored duty. Discounting witchcraft and a few ill-fated misfires, Grundel's Defenders have yet to lose one of their precious war machines to a foe - a matter of great pride to the regiment.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong style=\"text-align: right;\">- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Wissenland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Large Shield, Quality Polearm (Any)</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.UaDGF5MBFBwPq5YU]{Iron Jaw} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Black and Red</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>6. Helhunten's Redeemers</h2>\n<p>Led by zealous Witch Hunter Joseph von Helhunten, the Redeemers are Vampire hunters. Hailing from the region around Siegfriedhof in Stirland, the Redeemers shun the green and yellow of their home province, choosing instead black and tan. All members of the regiment have experienced loss at the hands of the Undead and have vowed revenge.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>The Redeemers bear neck-protecting armour and many carry ritual stakes. A Priest of Sigmar accompanies the unit as the fight is both physical and spiritual.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Stirland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Religious Symbol, Silver Bullets <em>or </em>Bolts <em>or </em>Arrows, Silvered Melee Weapon (Any), Wooden Stakes.</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E98mVLZgE8bX5vQW]{Hatred (Undead)} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Black and Tan</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>7. Seahawks</h2>\n<p>One of Nordland's more celebrated regiments, the Seahawks comprised over two dozen companies at arms. The Seahawks were often the first regiment assigned to other states, and therefore received better weaponry than other troops, and drew higher pay. This was not an act of altruism on their Elector's part, but pride. The Count loathed sending forces to other lands, and was determined that his forces should outshine those of his rivals.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Nordland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Best Quality Halberd</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.BlHVzfs0Ow6IYEDw]{Furious Assault} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Blue and Yellow</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>8. Sterntower Marksmen</h2>\n<p>The Sterntower Marksmen are a newly formed regiment out of Steingart. They are garrisoned as part of the line of sentry post and signal towers that guard the low foothills of the eastern Wissenland, under the shadow of the imposing Black Mountains. Always at the ready to launch their signal flares to signify invasions, the watchtowers are essential for border defence.</p>\n<p>The Marksmen share the Sterntower with several other Imperial regiments - Halberdiers and Spearmen - with whom they have established a front-line camaraderie. Sergeant-at-Arms Hans Schwarzblut is the tower officer, in command of the Sterntower Marksmen and a unit each of Halberdier and Spearmen. He is a veteran of many battles against marauding Orcs and his tight discipline keeps all the troops at high alert. Unwilling to sit and wait, Schwartzblut often orders patrols up into the narrow mountain passes.&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Wissenland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Signal Flares, Quality Handgun <em>or </em>Heavy Crossbow</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.cygaI9gq4BQJvbB5]{Sniper} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Grey, White and Red</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>9. The Death's Heads</h2>\n<p>The halberdiers known as the Death's Heads were founded during the Vampire Wars. They began in the town of Essen, Ostermark during the rule of Vlad von Carstein. Those who dared to speak up against Vlad, let alone partake in armed resistance, soon disappeared, so in order to protect their identities, the first Death's Heads wore skulls as masks.</p>\n<p>The Death's Heads became famous after freeing Essen during a rebellion. Later, they took part in the Battle of Hel Fenn. Today the Death's Heads recruit not only from Essen, but all over Ostermark.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Their heraldry is maroon, and they have skulls on their shields. Even today, they still retain their trademark skull masks.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Ostermark</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Metal Skull Mask, Quality Halberd <em>or </em>Large Shield</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.8pVzgPkgWpTJvfhG]{Fearless (Undead)} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Black, Red and Yellow</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>10. The Swords of Ulric</h2>\n<p>The Swords of Ulric, also known as the <em>Sons of Ulric</em>, are a Middenland regiment of Swordsmen raised by the Cult of Ulric.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The formidable training of the Swords of Ulric consists not of marches or military drills, but instead on patrols and war parties led out of the city itself and into the hazardous regions of the Drakwald Forest, where they hunt out the tribes of beastmen that have taken residence in the land. Initiates hoping to join this famed regiment must accompany such excursions into the forest; only those that fight with honour (and survive) in the gruesome endeavour shall be admitted into the regiment.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>It is left to each soldier to equip himself in the blue and white colours of Middenland, but once he becomes a full member, most of the funding for equipment and supplies are administered by the Temple of Ulric. Since the regiment's founding, in the days when Count Mandred Skavenslayer rallied the Empire behind him and became Emperor, the Sons of Ulric have borne yellow shields into battle, a tradition that still hold true today. Also by tradition, each shield must bear a variation of the same device; a red wolf, signifying Ulric embattled. The grim northerners have little room for formal ceremony, but what they lack in parade-ground discipline, they make up for with uncommon savagery and dedication on the battlefield.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Middenland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Quality Sword <em>or </em>Axe <em>or </em>Hammer, Yellow Shield with Ulric&rsquo;s Symbol.</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RWJrupj9seau0w31]{Strike to Injure} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Blue and White</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>12. Van Klumpf's Buccaneers</h2>\n<p>Van Klumpf's Buccaneers, also known as<strong> </strong><em>The Murderers out of Marienburg</em> and The Scourge of the Reik are a notorious mercenary regiment in the Empire.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Their origins are unclear, however its generally thought that they originated in Marienburg due to their uniforms, which display the colors of the city-state. One theory states that Bartolomeus van Klumpf, the leader of the regiment, is the dispossessed son of a Marienburg noble. Since they arrived in Altdorf in 2545, they have become well-known for brutality. Their reputation has increased greatly over the years, but so has their fee. The Buccaneers are equipped with time-worn weapons and drab clothing, but are nevertheless an effective fighting force. Their are yellow, blue, and red and their device is the Ripper Fish.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Marienburg</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Any Exotic Item, 100 GC</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Ij9N3G8jzxb4lrwy]{Sea Legs} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Red, Blue and Yellow</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>13. Von Kragsburg Guard</h2>\n<p>The Von Kragsburg Guard are an Averland regiment of freelance Imperial soldiers funded and equipped by House Von Kragsburg, in the interest of protecting and ensuring the overall safety of trade along the Old Dwarf Road in exchange for a exorbitant fee. The patriarch of the noble family, Duke Bertold Von Kragsburg, also known as the \"Dirty Duke\", like his father before him, was forever seeking the glitter of gold in all its forms and value, seeking any avenue to ensure his wealth would grow ten-fold upon the climax of his endevour.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>As such, when the price is right the Von Kragsburg Guard have safeguarded merchants along the Old Dwarf Road for years, joined armies staving off invaders seeking to plunder Wissenland, and led expeditions to destroy Beastmen strongholds in the Great Forest region of Talabecland. Having a distingushed military career, the regiment have always fought for their home province of Averland, but such was their need for material wealth has ensured that these dealings are always been under a certain contract of payment. While the scruples of the \"Dirty Duke\" may be questioned, none may contest the regiments combat prowess. Countless tales prevail about their couragous actions on the battlefield, from withstanding charges from a horde of Goblin Wolf Riders on the plains of Averland to battling towering Ogres in the Worlds Edge Mountains, the proud Von Kragsburg Guard will always get the job, and always expect their employers to pay up.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Province:&nbsp;</strong>Averland</p>\n<p><strong>Trappings:&nbsp;</strong>Any Two Rare Items, 50 GC</p>\n<p><strong>Talent:&nbsp;</strong>You gain the @Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.talents-nom.1Y6Fu7uAsItBBYsl]{Dog of War} Talent</p>\n<p><strong>Uniform Colors:&nbsp;</strong>Yellow and Black</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.Ysz28jH2Y4Yt1Ogz"}}}
{"_id":"laqxe00loNZEVMC9","name":"Veteran Talents","permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.IYvqpriNiNutsvaa"}},"content":"<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Veteran Talents</h1>\n<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"modules\\nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e\\art\\veteran.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"513\" /></p>\n<p>To survive and triumph on the battlefields of the Empire requires truly exceptional individuals; men and women who stand head-and-shoulder above their peers to lead the Emperor&rsquo;s armies into glorious battle. It is not enough to merely know how to fire a handgun or command a unit of soldiers or knights to charge into battle; a true warrior must rise above the rank-and-file, showing themselves to be unique and exceptional. This is the role that these Talents play, advanced martial and military techniques not taught in the traditional manner through Careers, but through mud and blood, taught by the most grizzled veterans who have seen hell and back through years of fighting.</p>\n<p>Obtaining these Talents requires the character to Consult an Expert (WHFRP Core Book, page 197) with trainers as determined by the GM to be most suitable for training the Talent: Soldiers, Knights, Pit Fighters, Witch Hunters, etc. Once the trainer has been obtained the character must follow up with an Unusual Learning Endeavour (WHFRP Core Book, page 199-200) in order to acquire these advanced combat Talents.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>List of Veteran Talents :</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.VANOdNWFo3P9gzxg]{Ambusher}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.QjBPhJr6L3c2TMIn]{Armor-Monger}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.ClCysnqhJTh8FE8Q]{Blind Fighter}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.YsiPBxZ3kD9rviNA]{Bombardier}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.xDEf1fhzhs4tyBGI]{Crazed Cook}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.RQ8KI3q2n61ZssBJ]{Creative Fighter}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.2jGP3xJgARI3AEbI]{Crippling Blow}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.lheO9kUQD7NKjOj2]{Guardian}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.aJA3QqdN2xXQFaV1]{Hammer Swing}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.tDCneZPhhmW4i9bF]{Killing Strikes}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.ijvxbPdaMBblJ3b2]{Overkill}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.sHk3OncCfHj6hU4L]{Quick Draw}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.v2x3DYSwdj2sK9Bf]{Thunderous Charge}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.cB6CCW3aU02tH2MW]{Tireless}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.o7uGMfttFKzu6AyW]{True Grit}</li>\n<li>@Compendium[nations-of-mankind-wfrp4e.veterantalents-nom.dzuzDXPEgZs5w1El]{Volley Shot}</li>\n</ul>"}
{"_id":"siN4XGTmiQTSMBuX","name":"New Origins for Human Characters","content":"<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Warhammer Nations</h1>\n<p>All Nation Races are intended for use for all careers, not just the homebrew careers. All Characters are assumed to be fluent in Reikspiel, the language of the Empire, and their native tongue based on their nation of origin, and do not need to take it as a Skill. A Character who plays a Merchant from Araby is expected to speak Arabyan without any issues.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Albion</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Araby</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Bretonnia</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Cathay</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Estalia</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Ind</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Kislev</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Nippon</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Norsca</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Southlands</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Strigany</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Tilea</strong></h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3><strong>Westerland &amp; Marienburg</strong></h3>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\n<h2>1. Albion</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Albion is a small, windswept island off the coast of Norsca in the Great Ocean. It is said that it rains every day in Albion, that the islands are shrouded in mist and heavy fog while the land is predominantly bogs, marshes and fens. This damp and gloomy environment is inhabited by tribes of woad-wearing humans, led by Truthsayers, guardians of the mysterious Ogham Stones, and inhabited by creatures such as Giants and the strange Fimirs.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>A Tilean explorer and conqueror,&nbsp; Curious Gesar, the so-called First Citizen of Remas, at one time reached the shores of the misty islands and tried to bring the native barbarians his view of Tilean culture. He was unsuccessful, instead taking Hengus the Druid and the two biggest Giants of Albion with him as hostages. Back in Tilea he was assassinated and the Giants roam now the Old World&nbsp;as mercenaries.<sup id=\"fn_3b_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>No truth to these stories has ever been proven, and the rumours of Albion remain little more than fantastic tales told by drunks to any who would listen. But then a new legend spread across the land. Sailors talked of an island which had suddenly appeared to the far north. Huge white cliffs loomed out from the sea but the sailors had also spied beaches where a small boat may possibly make a landing. It would seem that the mists had parted and the land lay open to explore. Every race across the world gathered its armies to seek the treasures of Albion and claim the island as their own.<sup id=\"fn_3b_back\"></sup></p>\n<p><strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.LGHozP5gmQ8cuDQV]{Athletics}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.sRuMlaPU5xdIrwhd]{Climb}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.CcNJsS4jSwB6Ug1J]{Endurance}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.I0yPc4PH5erWJLmu]{Intimidate}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Albion)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Beasts or Monsters)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.PzimjNx9Ojq4g6mV]{Melee (Polearm)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.os4NKy5Oy6sRt1eh]{Outdoor Survival}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.NSnpJQiky8JcMnme]{Ranged (Throwing)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Xk5tp3aasPNtk4zt]{Stealth (Rural)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.vMYEkrWj0ip6ZOdv]{Resistance (Mutations)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.spdiWsONKTzkLbg3]{Stone Soup}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.1dUizIgLBgn4jICC]{Strider (Marshes)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Zf0vk2rjllpDh0Ua]{Very Strong} <em>or @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RmY0CUjiFYZ3GEKY]{Very Resilient}</em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>2. Araby</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The kingdom of Araby encompasses the regions bordering the great desert north of the Southlands. It is a land of contrasts, where the people are both devout and godless. Exotic and extravagant cities where massive vaulted palaces, full of wealth beyond the imagination of the dwarfs, loom over adobe and stucco houses in winding streets. Its cheerful and bustling nights, street performers, music, alcohol, narcotics, fiery food and concubines make Araby a charming and irresistible place for many travelers. These islands of civilization are isolated by vast expanses of arid badlands and suffocating deserts. It is a land where few ideas are forbidden and where human sciences and philosophy rival even the elves of Ulthuan in sophistication. Sun-bleached ruins stand as reminders of the tumultuous past of Araby, but the invaders of old are the partners of today and almost all languages of the known world can be heard in the streets of its ports and bazaars.</p>\n<p>Even united under the distant rule of the Great Sultan, the people of Araby are a disparate lot. The coastal Arabyans live in relatively fertile lands and have built some of the most wonderous cities of the world. They are educated, often multilingual and open to foreign cultures. The Arabyans of the hinterlands are hardier folks, used to surviving in the desert where almost no water or shade can be found and heat is pervasive. They are a mystical and harsh people, shaped by their home desert and daily struggles for survival.</p>\n<p>However, the apparent prosperity of the land conceals many problems. Often enough, a sorcerer oversteps one of the few taboos and delves into the forbidden arts. Nomad bandits scour the desert, and are but the least of many threats a traveler may encounter across the expanses of Araby. Ancient curses slumber in the ruins that dot the landscape while undead remnants of past wars still wander the desert or wait patiently beneath unsuspecting cities. The mysterious ratmen are still rumored to monitor the evolution of Araby from their lairs in the mountains, and secret cults to blasphemous deities lurk in the deepest valleys and ruins.&nbsp;<strong>- Kingdom of the Shifting Sands</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.fdq3RFSOKl5b3WzW]{Art ( Any)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.bSWoV1IiS5qWNw39]{Evaluate}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Indan or Southlander)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.X16IoUlKcVLI4MRw]{Language (Wastelander)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (City State)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.zZUX7wO4rOo8k9F0]{Navigation}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.9xR9uO8FIvi4YsJp]{Pray}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MeXCAQ3wqJzX07X7]{Ride (Camel or Horse)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.n8IfmLt4kzMhIKIv]{Sail (Xebec or Dhow or Felucca)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.7bZjB82f6LSkeczP]{Nimble Fingered}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GogGbYxkVdCmiKqf]{Read/Write}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GRRN3XAKIpEVCY7z]{Craftsman (Any)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.vMYEkrWj0ip6ZOdv]{Resistance (Heat)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.1dUizIgLBgn4jICC]{Strider (Deserts)}, <strong>City State Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><strong>City State Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Copher: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.34EBUkHQkrqF1sq7]{Briber}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.epPBu7x6BRWp2PHG]{Dealmaker}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>El-Kalabad: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.wBhPFggGqIXwbx1r]{Alley Cat}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.9sMAf0xmehjEmUao]{Fast Hands}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Lashiek: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Ij9N3G8jzxb4lrwy]{Sea Legs}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.qZ4cFy6z482ZONuA]{Sturdy}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Martek: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GRRN3XAKIpEVCY7z]{Craftsman (Mining)}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Z91GFaT6FhEwyESU]{Tunnel Rat}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Sudenberg: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.726gbrANZt8OqXr5]{Linguistics}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.5QcrpLQWWrsbKR79]{Numismatics}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Antoch: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.5lcttqGToT54WFrl]{Marksman}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.traits.GwjvDLZz3PvK6xgs]{Prejudice (Bretonnians}</li>\n<li><strong>Sartosa: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.r180vP86SlwyJc8W]{Criminal}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Nomad: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.spdiWsONKTzkLbg3]{Stone Soup}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>3. Bretonnia</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The Kingdom of Bretonnia, also known as the Land of Chivalry, is a highly martial feudal kingdom that lies between the lands of the Grey Mountains and the Great Ocean. Bretonnia is second only in size to that of the Empire, both their chief rival and closest ally, having a culture and society that revolves around the ideals of nobility, social birthright, and the upholding of a strictly enforced code of chivalry.</p>\n<p>Ruled by a Royarch,<a title=\"Royarch\" href=\"https://warhammerfantasy.fandom.com/wiki/Royarch\">&nbsp;</a>the nation of Bretonnia has been known throughout the kingdoms of man for having the greatest Knights in the entire Old World, even surpassing that of the Knightly orders of the Empire. A proud and honourable kingdom, the armies of Bretonnia are comprised mostly of knights and noblemen, who ride into battle with lance, horse, and sword, seeking glory and rooting out injustice wherever they go. The Knights of Bretonnia are trained to fight from childhood, and even the lowliest knights errant are considered superior to ordinary warriors. Their skills are further enhanced through constant training, battles and tournaments. It is not only Bretonnia's knights who are famed, however, for the kingdom also boasts the finest human sailors in the World. With their great sails billowing in the wind, Bretonnia's mighty fleets are&nbsp;a majestic sight on the high seas. Due to this regime, the combined military might of Bretonnia has surpassed that of even the greatest armies in history.</p>\n<p>Bretonnia is widely considered to be the fairest and most beautiful land in all the Old World. It is a green land of fertile farms, rolling hills, starkly beautiful mountains, and airy forests. Bretonnian chefs are famous for their culinary skills, and the wine produced in the vineyards of the country is renowned throughout the world. It is seen as a land of honour and virtue, where noble knights keep the domain safe as peasants till the fields, where chivalrous heroes slay monsters and rescue fair damsels. This is the image Bretonnians want to project, and it is not entirely false.&nbsp;<strong> - Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><em><strong>Peasantry</strong></em></h3>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.4IGdIhnwTaZijzg7]{Charm Animal}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.CcNJsS4jSwB6Ug1J]{Endurance}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Dukedom)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Agriculture)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZQSm2AwrgT2cHG0C]{Ranged (Bow)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oSbEE6eXH1S3LfUU]{Ride (Horse)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.wKwel9MG7NIG3i3w]{Trade (Farmer)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.7bZjB82f6LSkeczP]{Nimble Fingered} <em>or</em> &nbsp;@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RmY0CUjiFYZ3GEKY]{Very Resilient}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.spdiWsONKTzkLbg3]{Stone Soup}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.FF41XPboORgyDNsv]{Strong Back}, <strong>Dukedom Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><em><strong>Nobility</strong></em></h3>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.4IGdIhnwTaZijzg7]{Charm Animal}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Any)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oMaJZ5cvCJeOUq9H]{Leadership}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Dukedom)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Politics)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Lst4xxUcxTYMlD3U]{Melee (Two-Handed)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.9xR9uO8FIvi4YsJp]{Pray}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oSbEE6eXH1S3LfUU]{Ride (Horse)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.1IVGksL10N7GVrw3]{Noble Blood}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GogGbYxkVdCmiKqf]{Read/Write}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born},&nbsp;<strong>Dukedom Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><strong>Dukedom Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>L'Anguille:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.epPBu7x6BRWp2PHG]{Dealmaker}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.L74MT9BDwE4CfutY]{Old Salt}, @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Aquitaine:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.JLzJws09GMw9GWBV]{Coolheaded}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Artois: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E98mVLZgE8bX5vQW]{Hatred (Beastmen)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RmY0CUjiFYZ3GEKY]{Very Resilient}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Zf0vk2rjllpDh0Ua]{Very Strong}</li>\n<li><strong>Bastonne:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.IogM5gnsoOX63w7j]{Stout-hearted}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Bordeleaux:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.hTgrGkWnmIR4xhVe]{Carouser}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Ij9N3G8jzxb4lrwy]{Sea Legs}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Brionne:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.2eq8Ejotk54AZYwX]{Artistic}&nbsp;<em>or </em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.pQjZdMJDDaz0DpAD]{Perfect Pitch}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Carcassonne:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Couronne:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GRRN3XAKIpEVCY7z]{Craftsman (Farrier)}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.FjTnaxixsu1ShNNr]{Trick Riding}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Gisoreux:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.jQmIu8P85tF0njmD]{Seasoned Traveller}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.1dUizIgLBgn4jICC]{Strider (Mountains)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Lyonesse:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LzgxyMknSHjSkkeQ]{Cat-tongued}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.b4x1qEWcevX7xK58]{Schemer}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Montfort:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zImcTgEl2XNnbu5W]{Hardy}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Mousillon:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Ywo6fZNPC4zbHHSQ]{Strong-minded}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Parravon:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.9fq6p9Q6H02LjaSi]{Animal Affinity}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.mNoCuaVbFBflfO6X]{Sixth Sense}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Quenelles:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E98mVLZgE8bX5vQW]{Hatred (Greenskins)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>4. Cathay</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Past the Worlds Edge Mountains and across the Great Skull Lands, on the other side of the Mountains of Mourn and the vast steppes, begin the uncharted lands. Only a single path travels to the east, known as the Silk Road. It runs through the untamed steppes until its destination, the fabled kingdom of Cathay. The lure of the Silk Road is great to the merchant houses of Tilea and the Burgomeisters of the Empire, as well as the traders of Araby. But the road is far from safe: roving bandits, steppe nomads, and the vast Hobgoblin hordes of Hobgobla-Khan who rule the steppes are an ever-present threat, and one that cannot be taken too lightly. Only one caravan out of ten makes the trip safely.</p>\n<p>The travellers that return from Cathay tell tales of great golden pagodas and the inexhaustible armies of the eastern despots. They bring exotic spices and finest silks, gleaming gold, luxurious porcelain vases and all manner of strange and wonderful items from the Kingdom of the Dragon, glimpses of the mysterious glory of the distant and rich orient.</p>\n<p>They also bring tales of jade cities and high temples where mystics probe the movements of the heavenly bodies and the positions of the stars, of the scholars who inscribe every word ever uttered by their divine Emperor. Many strange creatures are said to live in the land of Cathay, from serpentine dragons to gigantic living stone dogs which guard the temples of the multitudinous gods of Cathay.</p>\n<p>Records of travellers tell of the thousand, thousand footsoldiers of the Emperor, the mystic brotherhoods of monks who can kill you with a touch of their hand, and the strange monkey warriors living high in the Mountains of Heaven.</p>\n<p>Most of these tales are highly fanciful, but certainly the Empire of the Celestial Dragon must be a wondrous and rich place, but until the trade routes to the east are safe it will remain a realm of legend.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.fdq3RFSOKl5b3WzW]{Art ( Any)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.sRuMlaPU5xdIrwhd]{Climb}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (indan)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Nipponese)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.X16IoUlKcVLI4MRw]{Language (Wastelander)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oMaJZ5cvCJeOUq9H]{Leadership}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Province)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZQSm2AwrgT2cHG0C]{Ranged (Bow)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.JLzJws09GMw9GWBV]{Coolheaded}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.QsrXxGZiHjth7RMg]{Savvy}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GogGbYxkVdCmiKqf]{Read/Write}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.726gbrANZt8OqXr5]{Linguistics}, <strong>Provincial Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><strong>Provincial Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Weijin: </strong>Three @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Nan-Gau:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GRRN3XAKIpEVCY7z]{Craftsman (Engineering)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Fu-Chow:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.1kgHcImgfyKI1IYp]{Fisherman}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Ij9N3G8jzxb4lrwy]{Sea Legs}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Shang-Yang:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Xianbei: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E98mVLZgE8bX5vQW]{Hatred (Skavens)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Yuanjin: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.JLzJws09GMw9GWBV]{Coolheaded}, Two @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Han Kuo:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RmY0CUjiFYZ3GEKY]{Very Resilient}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Zf0vk2rjllpDh0Ua]{Very Strong}, Two @Table[talents]</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>5. Estalia</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The Estalian Kingdoms lie in the south of the Old World, a warmer and drier area than the north. The threat of Chaos seems very remote here, far away from the incursions and beyond the immediate threat of Chaos Bands. Unlike Bretonnia and the Empire, which are unified nations under a single ruler, the Estalian Kingdoms are many and of various sizes. <sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>The kingdoms of the Irrana Mountains are home to fierce, tough hill-fighters, while those along the south coast are prosperous trading nations whose ships ply the Southern Sea to Araby. The largest cities and towns war upon each other, as well as against the Arabyans to the south, the Bretonnians to the north and the Tileans to the east.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Today, the two most powerful kingdoms are the city-states of&nbsp; Bilbali and Magritta. Both are strong because of trade and access to the sea, a fact that causes much jealousy amongst the poor kingdoms of the Irrana Mountains. <strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong><sup id=\"fn_6b_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.LGHozP5gmQ8cuDQV]{Athletics}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.d3VZwO4Y5JH5DXdT]{Bribery}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.R2ytluHiEFF2KQ5e]{Consume Alcohol}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.qBm2fu3oMhxsDBNQ]{Entertain (Storytelling)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.5EvSIh1khpt77uM7]{Language (Bretonnian)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.12e3H6NX4JH0bwI3]{Language (Tilean)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Arabyan)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Region)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.HO8vIjGTHjmenIaV]{Perform (Jota)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rvd0S8Z0v2m0MHmD]{Sleight of Hand}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.AcnFuDKRemLI9ey7]{Nose for Trouble}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.QsrXxGZiHjth7RMg]{Savvy}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave},&nbsp;<strong>Region Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><strong>Region Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Arad&oacute;n: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.JLzJws09GMw9GWBV]{Coolheaded}, Two @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Catilinia:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LzgxyMknSHjSkkeQ]{Cat-tongued}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Vanlen:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.8lSoPDGrmeTIaapm]{Gregarious}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Navarr:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LU6Ycl5z4kp1Wr04]{Mimic}, Two<strong> </strong>@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Castill:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.IogM5gnsoOX63w7j]{Stout-hearted}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Laon: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zImcTgEl2XNnbu5W]{Hardy}, Two @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Gaellica:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.fEFAMNqh8nJIfBkM]{Field Dressing}, Two @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Vasconia:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.BbStIySkF1hDM2zq]{Lightning Reflexes}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.0hn6UaKq8CoZP2zD]{Menacing}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Andal:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GRRN3XAKIpEVCY7z]{Craftsman (Trade)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GogGbYxkVdCmiKqf]{Read/Write}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Murc:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.5KP9sOoLSGvj9EXp]{Beneath Notice}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Portul:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.oQzTJEXUx28sCiH3]{Sharp}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GogGbYxkVdCmiKqf]{Read/Write}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Sartosa:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.r180vP86SlwyJc8W]{Criminal}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>6. Ind</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The closest of the three human-populated lands of the east is Ind.<sup id=\"fn_13a_back\"></sup> Exotic spices, jade and other treasures lure the adventurous to this sweltering realm, although few return. Some fall prey to bestial creatures on the route to Ind, others are captured and sacrificed by bloodthirsty cults. However, travellers that do return report that the rulers of Ind are wealthy and generous, living in opulent palaces surrounded by slaves and servants, and are great patrons of the arts and Ind's many golden temples.<sup id=\"fn_6b_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>A deeply spiritual land, its people may seem strangely content to outsiders, but it is just their odd way of dealing with the horrors of life and should not distract the traveller from the perils of this place. A favoured destination for spice merchants from all across the world, who eagerly travel there to buy rare and valued herbs, it can be difficult to understand the customs of the locals. In fact, doing something as simple as crossing a bridge the wrong way, or eating meat can stir up the ire of the locals in some places, bringing down swift retribution upon the confused traveller. The gods of Ind are also a puzzling lot, and travellers are advised to smile politely and nod, as a local offers up prayers to his mouse or weevil deity, all the while content in the knowledge that Sigmar could crush them had he half a mind.<sup id=\"fn_13a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Many are the tales of wonder told by spice merchants returned from the lands to the east of the Old World, but few such yarns can be as bizarre as the accounts of the creatures said to reside in the verdant rainforests of central Ind. The lands of Ind are rich and fertile, and ruled by aristocratic overlords from their gorgeous palaces. Yet the people are poor and superstitious, and revere a staggering array of gods and spirits, leaving offerings and saying prayers to them ceaselessly as they go about their day.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong><sup id=\"fn_5a_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.CcNJsS4jSwB6Ug1J]{Endurance}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Arabyan)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Cathayan)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.X16IoUlKcVLI4MRw]{Language (Wastelander)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Kingdom)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.NSnpJQiky8JcMnme]{Ranged (Throwing)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.BbStIySkF1hDM2zq]{Lightning Reflexes}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.u0CFf3xwiyidD9T5]{Luck}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.vMYEkrWj0ip6ZOdv]{Resistance (Heat)}&nbsp;<em>or</em> One @Table[talents],&nbsp;<strong>Kingdom Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><strong>Kingdom Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Kingdom of Bhalluka:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E98mVLZgE8bX5vQW]{Hatred (Daemons)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Kingdom of Gandharva:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.wNvPXAhlKABl6hpk]{Pure Soul},&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Kingdom of Singha:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.9CAkY3SQjQxRTlNJ]{Roughrider}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.jQmIu8P85tF0njmD]{Seasoned Traveller}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Kingdom of Lakshana:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.2eq8Ejotk54AZYwX]{Artistic}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.7bZjB82f6LSkeczP]{Nimble Fingered}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Kingdom of Panchala:&nbsp;</strong>Two @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Kingdom of Kosala:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.epPBu7x6BRWp2PHG]{Dealmaker}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Kingdom of Kurya:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>7. Kislev</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The Kingdom of Kislev is the most northerly Human civilisation within the Old World,<sup id=\"fn_2a_back\"></sup> a powerful and war-driven nation that is known far and wide for having some of the greatest horsemen to ever roam the plains of the southern realms. From the Worlds Edge Mountains to the East and the Sea of Claws&nbsp;in the West, Kislev stands at the very frontiers of Human civilisation, a land covered in wide-open steppes and thundering icy rivers, where lonely villages stand isolated in the empty wilderness, while mighty cities rise from the landscape like great islands of stone. The climate is harsh and unforgiving, and only the strongest, most determined people can survive here.<sup id=\"fn_1b_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>The inhabitants of Kislev are these very same people, a race of wolf-tough and self-reliant warriors, valiant and determined in the defense of their homeland against the hated marauders of the uppermost North.<sup id=\"fn_1b_back\"></sup>Ruled by a mighty Tzar, <sup id=\"fn_1g_back\"></sup>Kislev is a nation born from the saddle, their peoples ancestry being traced to the mighty horse-warriors of the Eastern Steppes many millennia ago.</p>\n<p><sup id=\"fn_1j_back\"></sup>Since the founding of this mighty kingdom, Kislev has been, since its very creation, under siege by the murderous Hordes of Chaos Undivided, a kingdom that sits forever at the brink of total annihilation. Countless generations of Kislevites have fought, bled, and died in the snowy tundra of those harsh northern lands, and it is thanks to these brave Kislevite warriors that the Kingdoms of Men have managed to flourish in the south, huddled together in their warm and safe homes, whilst the Sons of Kislev fight till they draw their last dying breath.<sup id=\"fn_1j_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Kislev is a country forged from various warring invaders who finally settled alongside each other. The bulk of the nation&rsquo;s population is mostly made up of two tribal people, the Ungols of the north and the Gospodars of the south, while the remaining population consist of the Norse, and the last remnants of the <a class=\"new\" title=\"Ropsmenn (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvUm9wc21lbm4/YWN0aW9uPWVkaXQmcmVkbGluaz0x\">Ropsmenn</a> people. Tribes such as the Dolgan have migrated from the Eastern Steppes and made their new homes in Kislev&rsquo;s northern borders, while many of the people that inhabits the south display many traits of the Empire, as it is common for people in this region to interact and mingle the bloodlines.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><em><strong>Gospodar</strong></em></h3>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.4IGdIhnwTaZijzg7]{Charm Animal}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.bSWoV1IiS5qWNw39]{Evaluate}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.fPVnjkCnm5nKdKBh]{Language (Norse)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.X16IoUlKcVLI4MRw]{Language (Wastelander)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Ungol)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Kislev)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZQSm2AwrgT2cHG0C]{Ranged (Bow)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oSbEE6eXH1S3LfUU]{Ride (Horse)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.vMYEkrWj0ip6ZOdv]{Resistance (Cold)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.QsrXxGZiHjth7RMg]{Savvy}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Zf0vk2rjllpDh0Ua]{Very Strong}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}, <strong>Provincial Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><em><strong>Ungol</strong></em></h3>\n<p><strong>Skills:</strong> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.4IGdIhnwTaZijzg7]{Charm Animal}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.iYan4z52v7HYM9u9]{Drive}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.I0yPc4PH5erWJLmu]{Intimidate}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Gospodarinyi)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Kislev)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.os4NKy5Oy6sRt1eh]{Outdoor Survival}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZQSm2AwrgT2cHG0C]{Ranged (Bow)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oSbEE6eXH1S3LfUU]{Ride (Horse)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents: </strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zImcTgEl2XNnbu5W]{Hardy}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>One @Table[talents], @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.vMYEkrWj0ip6ZOdv]{Resistance (Cold)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.5lcttqGToT54WFrl]{Marksman}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RmY0CUjiFYZ3GEKY]{Very Resilient},&nbsp;<strong>Provincial Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><strong>Provincial Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Northern Kislev:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.x0WMGwuQzReXcQrs]{Night Vision}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Eastern Kislev (Praag):&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Ywo6fZNPC4zbHHSQ]{Strong-minded}, One&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Western Kislev (Erengrad):&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.L74MT9BDwE4CfutY]{Old Salt}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Ij9N3G8jzxb4lrwy]{Sea Legs}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Southern Kislev (City of Kislev):&nbsp;</strong>Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>8. Nippon</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The inscrutable Eastern empire known as Nippon is ruled by a reclusive semi-divine Emperor<sup id=\"fn_4b_back\"></sup>, also known as the <a class=\"new\" title=\"Divine Sun (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvRGl2aW5lX1N1bj9hY3Rpb249ZWRpdCZyZWRsaW5rPTE=\">Divine Sun</a><sup id=\"fn_9h_back\"></sup>, but real power lies in the hands of the many feudal warlords or 'Samurai'<sup id=\"fn_4b_back\"></sup>, knights resplendent in brightly coloured armour made of lacquered wood that enforce a complex and rigid class system.<sup id=\"fn_10a_back\"></sup> These warrior nobles govern large domains and command retinues with which they frequently indulge in private wars among themselves. Nippon is an island realm and a notable sea power and it sometimes happens that a Samurai war fleet is dispersed by a typhoon, scattering the ships far and wide. Should an isolated war junk fetch up on a foreign shore the Samurai commander will gather his men and march straight for the nearest representative of authority to offer his service in return for food and shelter. Sometimes Samurai Lords deliberately embark their followers into war junks and set sail towards the rising sun in search of adventure, especially if the other feudal clans back home in Nippon are cramping his style.<sup id=\"fn_4b_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>The Samurai classes dominate Nipponese society. Their land is so vast and so often inhospitable, the Samurai so strong and the Emperor so weak, that central control has all but disappeared. Society is normally run by the Samurai, who exchange their protection for control over the towns and cities, along with taxes and the right to levy militias. As the Samurai have grown in strength, so has each settlement's need for the Samurai. The Samurai's training, devotion and continual practice have turned them into awesome fighters.<sup id=\"fn_3a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Nippon abounds with diverse orders of monks, either martial or clerical. The Orders select their members at a very early age and the chosen ones devote their entire lives to philosophy, theology and the martial arts. A lifetime of gruelling study hones their bodies and minds to a very fine edge.<sup id=\"fn_3a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Nipponese are said to be intensely distrustful of outsiders -- they only permit foreigners to travel in their lands rarely, and so little else is known about Nippon, though doubtless if the rest of the world is anything to go by, it will be populated by its own unique and deadly monsters and perils.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong><sup id=\"fn_10a_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Cathayan)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.X16IoUlKcVLI4MRw]{Language (Wastelander)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oMaJZ5cvCJeOUq9H]{Leadership}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Nippon)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.ZQSm2AwrgT2cHG0C]{Ranged (Bow)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.n8IfmLt4kzMhIKIv]{Sail (Junk or Atakebune)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.hodHqFNKAmu40ajh]{Swim}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.mNoCuaVbFBflfO6X]{Sixth Sense}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.oQzTJEXUx28sCiH3]{Sharp},&nbsp;<strong>Clan Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><strong>Clan Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Northern Clans:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}, Two @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Eastern Clans:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.BbStIySkF1hDM2zq]{Lightning Reflexes}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Western Clans:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.QsrXxGZiHjth7RMg]{Savvy}, Two @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Southern Clans:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RmY0CUjiFYZ3GEKY]{Very Resilient}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>9. Norsca</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Norsca is a peninsula located in the far north of the Old World, lying on the doorstep of the Chaos Wastes itself.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup> It is bordered to the south by the frigid waters of the Sea of Claws, to the north by the <a class=\"new\" title=\"Kraken Sea (page does not exist)\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-uncrawlable-url=\"L3dpa2kvS3Jha2VuX1NlYT9hY3Rpb249ZWRpdCZyZWRsaW5rPTE=\">Kraken Sea</a> and the Realm of Chaos, and to the east by the roving Kurgan tribes of the Steppes.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Norsca is inhabited by a race of savage and ferocious Men known variously as<strong> </strong>Norscans, Norsemen or the Norse. Fur-clad warriors and berserkers of hairy brawn, these wrathful barbarians sail the seas in fearsome longships and unleash their devastating fury upon the south.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>he brutality of Norse raids has been felt as far abroad as the Witch King's baleful domain of Naggaroth, as well as the mysterious realm of mighty Cathay,<sup id=\"fn_35_back\"></sup> for the men of Norsca are reckoned to be perhaps the most adept sailors and navigators in all the world;<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup> unequaled by any in their courage and reckless thirst for conquest.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Despite their proximity to the Chaos Wastes, not all Norscans are worhippers of Chaos. The most southern tribes especially, like the Skaelings and the Bjornlings, shun mutations and are wary of the malignant corruptive influence of the Hound, the Serpent, the Crow and the Eagle.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.LGHozP5gmQ8cuDQV]{Athletics}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.sRuMlaPU5xdIrwhd]{Climb}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.R2ytluHiEFF2KQ5e]{Consume Alcohol}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.CcNJsS4jSwB6Ug1J]{Endurance}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.I0yPc4PH5erWJLmu]{Intimidate}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Norsca)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Lst4xxUcxTYMlD3U]{Melee (Two-Handed)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.os4NKy5Oy6sRt1eh]{Outdoor Survival}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Fs06sr7y9JKpVQmB]{Perception}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.n8IfmLt4kzMhIKIv]{Sail (Longship)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.hodHqFNKAmu40ajh]{Swim}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.x0WMGwuQzReXcQrs]{Night Vision}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.vMYEkrWj0ip6ZOdv]{Resistance (Cold)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Zf0vk2rjllpDh0Ua]{Very Strong}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born},&nbsp;<strong>Tribe Trait (Any) </strong><em>or&nbsp;</em>Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</p>\n<h3><strong>Tribe Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Aeslings Tribe:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.0hn6UaKq8CoZP2zD]{Menacing}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}</li>\n<li><strong>Baersonlings Tribe:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.qZ4cFy6z482ZONuA]{Sturdy}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.RmY0CUjiFYZ3GEKY]{Very Resilient}</li>\n<li><strong>Bjornlings Tribe:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.FF41XPboORgyDNsv]{Strong Back}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.Zf0vk2rjllpDh0Ua]{Very Strong}</li>\n<li><strong>Graelings Tribe:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.SgjJMBgc85aswvhm]{Relentless}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}</li>\n<li><strong>Sarls Tribe:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.BbStIySkF1hDM2zq]{Lightning Reflexes}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.1dUizIgLBgn4jICC]{Strider (Snow}</li>\n<li><strong>Skaelings Tribe:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.oQzTJEXUx28sCiH3]{Sharp}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.mNoCuaVbFBflfO6X]{Sixth Sense}</li>\n<li><strong>Skeggi Tribe:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.JLzJws09GMw9GWBV]{Coolheaded}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.vMYEkrWj0ip6ZOdv]{Resistance (Disease)}</li>\n<li><strong>Vargs Tribe:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.uRvOg8AnCcP2ufx8]{Resolute}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>10. Southlands</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The Southlands is a large, tropical continent located far to the south of the Old World, beyond the mysterious realm of Araby and the Land of the Dead. Its northern land mass is a barren wasteland of deserts, studded with dusty and deserted tomb-cities, while further south, it is a land of unspoiled jungle and swamp, isolated from the realms of Man, Elf and Dwarf for uncounted centuries.<sup id=\"fn_1a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Many brave or foolish explorers and treasure hunters &mdash; though the two are often indistinguishable &mdash; have attempted to penetrate the thick jungles that make up the majority of the southern region of this land, but almost all have never been seen or heard of again. Legends tell that the Southlands was once joined to the continent of Lustria, and this is borne out by the many identical species of flora and fauna indigenous to both.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.LGHozP5gmQ8cuDQV]{Athletics}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.sRuMlaPU5xdIrwhd]{Climb}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.CcNJsS4jSwB6Ug1J]{Endurance}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Arabyan)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Cathayan)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.PzimjNx9Ojq4g6mV]{Melee (Polearm)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.zZUX7wO4rOo8k9F0]{Navigation}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.os4NKy5Oy6sRt1eh]{Outdoor Survival}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Fs06sr7y9JKpVQmB]{Perception}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.NSnpJQiky8JcMnme]{Ranged (Throwing)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.BbStIySkF1hDM2zq]{Lightning Reflexes}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.AwUUEwwf2Vt4ksCN]{Sprinter}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.CV9btQn09S9Fn8Jk]{Strong Legs}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>One @Table[talents],&nbsp;<strong>Tribe trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><strong>Tribe Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Northern Southlands Tribes:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Lizardmen)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Eastern Southlands Tribes:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.IFKWu98qmWpaSfUi]{Ambidextrous}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.zGQ0ShUTSlUvVtWh]{Warrior Born}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Western Southlands Tribes:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.jrFIFLhyOYwcyMUl]{Flee!}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E98mVLZgE8bX5vQW]{Hatred (Undead)}, Two @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Southern Southlands Tribes:&nbsp;</strong>Three&nbsp;@Table[talents]</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>11. Strigany</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The human empire of Strigos worshipped Vampires as Gods, but their Undead deities couldn&rsquo;t save them from the might of butchering Greenskins. When the few escapees staggered north into the Old World, the stricken people met a wall of hatred from the other human tribes, but they had nowhere else to turn.</p>\n<p>They wander there still, now calling themselves the Strigany, and are hated no less, even though the centuries have erased the memories of their blood-soaked empire from the minds of their countrymen. Mirroring the rootless land caravans of their people, the Strigany meander up and down the River Reik in small boat communities, moving from one persecution to the next. Their dreary, poorly maintained vessels are often moored far from civilisation, where they prey on the superstitions of passing riverfolk by selling charms and wards for whatever coin they can.</p>\n<p>he people of Strigos were scattered to the winds when their lands were destroyed and have since taken up a nomadic life. They roam the Empire in caravan trains or river barges, making money where they can and stealing when they can't. Their history under the Vampires ensures they maintain their travelling lifestyle, marking them not just as thieves and cutthroats but also necromancers and servants of darkness. In truth, most of them are simple woodsmen, entertainers, or vagabonds, but a few do know something of witchcraft, a little of fortune telling, and a large amount of Vampire lore.</p>\n<p>These mystics were taught the true and complete history of their people, and they carry the secret knowledge from those ancient days, as well as the promise of their Strigos lords to one day return and lead them back to glory.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.MXy22hFCgntdlQrn]{Animal Care}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.4IGdIhnwTaZijzg7]{Charm Animal}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.UFunAopCNaD8Zdc7]{Entertain (Singing)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.qBm2fu3oMhxsDBNQ]{Entertain (Storytelling)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Any)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Local)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Spirits)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.HO8vIjGTHjmenIaV]{Perform (Any)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.bBLK2hznjPlby6Jb]{Play (Any)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.oSbEE6eXH1S3LfUU]{Ride (Horse)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.9fq6p9Q6H02LjaSi]{Animal Affinity}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.pQjZdMJDDaz0DpAD]{Perfect Pitch}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.jQmIu8P85tF0njmD]{Seasoned Traveller}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.oQzTJEXUx28sCiH3]{Sharp}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}, Two&nbsp;@Table[talents]</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>12. Tilea</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Tilea is a large fertile peninsula located within the southernmost border of the Old World, along the tranquil coast of the warm and bountiful Tilean Sea.<sup id=\"fn_1m_back\"></sup> The wealthy city-states that dot Tilea's landscape embrace the ideals of trade, exploration, progression and civil war with almost equal passion. Tilea is a land of great wealth and advancement, a land known far and wide for being the cradle from which the ideals of democracy, civil liberty and justice was birthed, founded, and established. <sup id=\"fn_1n_back\"></sup>It is only from here that the first true Republics were formed by the nation's people, such as the Republic of Remas, while others are ruled by a powerful caste of wealthy merchants, known collectively as the Merchant Princes.<sup id=\"fn_1k_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Yet for all its wealth and advancement, Tilea is, like much of the Old World, a fractious, war-torn region, where the fertile countryside becomes the battleground from which legions of mercenaries clash in titanic struggles that serve no purpose other than to advance the petty and greedy ambition of the rich and the few. As such, it should be no surprise that the greatest concentration of these gold-hungry cutthroats can be found in the lands of Tilea. Perhaps it is fitting that these mercenaries are known collectively as the Dogs of War.&nbsp;<strong>- Warhammer Wiki</strong><sup id=\"fn_1h_back\"></sup></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.fdq3RFSOKl5b3WzW]{Art ( Any)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.d3VZwO4Y5JH5DXdT]{Bribery}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.R2ytluHiEFF2KQ5e]{Consume Alcohol}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.qBm2fu3oMhxsDBNQ]{Entertain (Storytelling)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Emd8lVdIpaXTxLwL]{Language (Estalian)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.5EvSIh1khpt77uM7]{Language (Bretonnian)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Politics)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (City State)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.n8IfmLt4kzMhIKIv]{Sail (Caravel or Carrack or Galley or Galleass)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rvd0S8Z0v2m0MHmD]{Sleight of Hand}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.8lSoPDGrmeTIaapm]{Gregarious}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>One&nbsp;@Table[talents], @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GogGbYxkVdCmiKqf]{Read/Write}&nbsp;<em>Or </em>One @Table[talents], @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.oQzTJEXUx28sCiH3]{Sharp}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave},&nbsp;<strong>City State Trait (Any)</strong></p>\n<h3><strong>City States Traits :</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Remas:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Merchants)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Luccini:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Mymidians)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Trantio:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Artists)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Pavona:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Carpenters)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Verezzo:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Politicians)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Sartosa:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Pirates)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Miragliano:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Rat Catchers)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>Tobaro:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Miners)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n<li><strong>New World Colonies:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.sYbgpSnRqSZWgwFP]{Etiquette (Adventurers)}, One @Table[talents]</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>13. Westerland (Wasteland)</h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The Wasteland is a coastal area around the mouth of the River Reik which contains the prosperous city of Marienburg. The Wasteland used to be the Empire province of Westerland that was conquered in 501 IC by Emperor Sigismund II, until it seceded during the reign of Emperor Dieter IV in 2429 IC through a hefty bribe.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Marienburg is considered to be the largest trading hub in the Old World and is the greatest of its ports, far more wondrous than even the city-states of Tilea. Straddling the mouth of the River Reik as it drains the mainland into the Sea of Claws, nearly all maritime trade that concerns Bretonnia and the Empire happens here. It is a place of great wealth and great opportunity. It is a place despised by the Empire, despite its reliance on the fabulous port city&rsquo;s good fortunes.<sup id=\"fn_2a_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Marienburg is vast; a bright spot in an otherwise forlorn and wretched landscape. The people of the city are descended by the tribe of the Jutones, who drove the Endals and the Fimir off their lands and made the marshes their new found home. In fact, the people of Westerland are of Endal stock while the city itself is purely Jutones in origin. The city itself rises from the foetid swamp that typifies the Wasteland, that gloomy march between the impenetrable Drakwald Forest and the immense Pale Sisters. With the regular rains, sucking mires, and the strange breed of peasants that make their living trawling the dark waters of the countryside, reaching the grand city can sometimes be a feat in and of itself. A visitor to Marienburg can quickly be overwhelmed by the sheer size of this metropolis, with its innumerable islands, canals, and labyrinthine streets. So large is the city that many of its denizens rarely venture beyond their own districts, and can only speculate about what happens on the other side of the city.<sup id=\"fn_2b_back\"></sup></p>\n<p>Anyone wishing to get anywhere in the city must cough up a few coins to pay for passage on one of the canals. Certainly, one could get where they want to go on foot, but the streets are so narrow, so twisting, it&rsquo;s easy to get lost, swallowed whole by a city that always hungers for fresh meat. Thus the canals are the main thoroughfares and the murky waters, glistening with the oily sheen of filth, are filled with skiffs, rowboats, sailing ships, and even galleons come to pass through the city and venture onwards to Altdorf or even as far as Nuln.&nbsp;<strong>-Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.d3VZwO4Y5JH5DXdT]{Bribery}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.exLrBrn2mjb6x2Cq]{Charm}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pxNjTxsp1Kp0SmQe]{Cool}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.bSWoV1IiS5qWNw39]{Evaluate}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.RLQHm1s4IuY9RSr2]{Gossip}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.pKLMbmG3Ivt6mzMf]{Haggle}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Arabyan)}&nbsp;<em>or</em> @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.5EvSIh1khpt77uM7]{Language (Bretonnian)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Cathayan)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.XQiiwS9m2Du1IMUz]{Language (Nipponese)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Emd8lVdIpaXTxLwL]{Language (Estalian)}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.12e3H6NX4JH0bwI3]{Language (Tilean)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Westerland)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.n8IfmLt4kzMhIKIv]{Sail (Cog or Caravel or Carrack or Frigate or Barge)}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.wKwel9MG7NIG3i3w]{Trade (Any)}</p>\n<p><strong>Talents:&nbsp;</strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.34EBUkHQkrqF1sq7]{Briber}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.epPBu7x6BRWp2PHG]{Dealmaker}, @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.QsrXxGZiHjth7RMg]{Savvy}&nbsp;<em>or&nbsp;</em>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.LPgjE0cexTVOBVCY]{Suave}, Three @Table[talents]</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.ttaRocfnRUtFZHKK"}}}
{"_id":"tzy1NHdL585lectj","name":"Knightly Orders of the Empire","permission":{"default":0,"lNumE4kwYfzQkIkY":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.L9NXm9gAnzBtxFvM"}},"content":"<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Knightly Orders of the Empire</h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&ldquo;The Knightly Orders of the Empire are a heroic brotherhood of armored warriors who ride into battle atop mighty barded warhorses and sometimes other, more exotic creatures into battle. Knights are magnificent figures, clad in gleaming Full Plate Armor crafted by Dwarfen smiths, armed with weaponry of the finest quality. To become a Knight is also to become one of the most elite warriors the Empire has to offer.</p>\n<p>Because the cost of individual knightly training is prohibitively expensive, many sons of the Imperial nobility choose to join one of the many brotherhoods located throughout the Empire to progress through society, and as such, the Knightly Orders come in many different shape and sizes. Some of these Orders, like the Knights Griffon, only recruit from the local nobility, while others become templars of a particular Imperial deity, such as the zealous Knights of Sigmar's Blood or the Knights of the White Wolf. Some are well known throughout the Empire, while others are quite small, relatively unknown sects valiantly doing their part to make the Empire a safer place for Men to live.</p>\n<p>Although the common people might find little distinction between the many Knight Orders of the Empire, upon closer observation, one will realize that there are two distinct types of Knightly Orders within the Empire itself. These types are divided between the common Secular Orders (An Order of Knights with no specific allegiance to a Ruler or Religion), and a Templar Order (An Order founded for the purpose of servitude to a particular god).&rdquo;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><strong>&mdash;Warhammer Wiki</strong></p>\n<p>These bonuses are granted to those who select the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.career-descriptions.n2VdkCPNNxdupjeQ]{Knight} Career in the WFRP 4E Core Book and dedicate themselves to a specific order of knights. The bonuses increase as the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.career-descriptions.n2VdkCPNNxdupjeQ]{Knight} PC progresses in their career, starting from @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FrPCbQ7fq1Fchthn]{Squire} to @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.Esy17RVOZQw2gShT]{Knight of the Inner Circle}. Please consult the GM before making any homebrew modifications towards your character. Your character must originate from the Empire to qualify for these Orders.</p>\n<p>All Lore and Melee Skills, and Talents, granted to the knight by their Orders are treated as if added to their Knight Career and may be purchased and advanced as normal. If you leave your Order under any conditions, such as being excommunicated or leaving of your own will, you lose the ability to purchase the Talents available from your Order if not already purchased&mdash;similar to if you left your Career. If your Order grants you a special ability at your 4th Career Level as Knight of the Inner Circle and you leave, you lose the ability until you reenter your Knightly Order.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<h3>Order of the Blazing Sun</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Knights of the White Wolf</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Order of the Black Bear</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Knigts Griffon</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Knights Panther</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Grand Order of the Reiksguard</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Templars of the Everlasting Light</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Order of the Broken Sword</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Order of the Sacred Scythe</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Knights of Sigmar's Blood</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Knights of Morr</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Order of the Golden Lion</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Knights Encarmine</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Order of the Hammer of Sigmar</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Order of the Fiery Heart</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Order of the Black Rose</h3>\n</li>\n<li>\n<h3>Order of the Reikshammer</h3>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>1. Order of the Blazing Sun</h3>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FrPCbQ7fq1Fchthn]{Squire}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Mymidia)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FhK6JOd3LSTlHwoa]{Knight}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.PzimjNx9Ojq4g6mV]{Melee (Polearm)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.GPhqluMBhCeTnyNJ]{First Knight}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.VscjNv6RzHFb9CQp]{Enclosed Fighter} Talent.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.Esy17RVOZQw2gShT]{Knight of the Inner Circle}:</strong> Any Spears you wield automatically gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.BVZWihaal1zq3aJs]{Spear of Myrmidia} Miracle at the start of an encounter and lasts your Fellowship Bonus in rounds.</p>\n<p><strong>Heraldry:</strong> Black and Gold, The Sun Emblem.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>2. Knights of the White Wolf</h3>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FrPCbQ7fq1Fchthn]{Squire}:</strong>&nbsp;You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Ulric)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FhK6JOd3LSTlHwoa]{Knight}:</strong>&nbsp;You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Lst4xxUcxTYMlD3U]{Melee (Two-Handed)}.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.GPhqluMBhCeTnyNJ]{First Knight}:</strong>&nbsp;You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.oRx92ByVNEBN6YkK]{Berserk Charge} Talent.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.Esy17RVOZQw2gShT]{Knight of the Inner Circle}:</strong>&nbsp;Any Axes you wield automatically gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.prayers.rrfrmqCpy10u7c9o]{Winter's Bite} Miracle at the start of an encounter and lasts your Fellowship Bonus in rounds.</p>\n<p><strong>Heraldry:</strong>&nbsp;White and Gold, Fur-Pelts and Wolf Sigils.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>3. Order of the Black Bear</h3>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FrPCbQ7fq1Fchthn]{Squire}:</strong>&nbsp;You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Monsters)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FhK6JOd3LSTlHwoa]{Knight}:</strong>&nbsp;You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.PzimjNx9Ojq4g6mV]{Melee (Polearm)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.GPhqluMBhCeTnyNJ]{First Knight}:</strong>&nbsp;You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.8pVzgPkgWpTJvfhG]{Fearless (Monsters)} Talent.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.Esy17RVOZQw2gShT]{Knight of the Inner Circle}:</strong>&nbsp;You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.GOtpCOZ2br14GrBW]{Slayer} Talent.</p>\n<p><strong>Heraldry:</strong>&nbsp;Black and Red, Bear Paw Sigil.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>4. Knights Griffon</h3>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FrPCbQ7fq1Fchthn]{Squire}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Sigmar)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FhK6JOd3LSTlHwoa]{Knight}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.GPhqluMBhCeTnyNJ]{First Knight}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.FjTnaxixsu1ShNNr]{Trick Riding} Talent.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.Esy17RVOZQw2gShT]{Knight of the Inner Circle}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.uRvOg8AnCcP2ufx8]{Resolute} Talent and @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.yr4ikZaXnYt7kOZd]{Ride (Demigryph)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>Heraldry:</strong> Black and Yellow, with Blue, Green, and Burgundy Plumes, Griffon Sigil.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>5. Knights Panther</h3>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FrPCbQ7fq1Fchthn]{Squire}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Beastmen)} and @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Mutants)} Skills.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FhK6JOd3LSTlHwoa]{Knight}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Lst4xxUcxTYMlD3U]{Melee (Two-Handed)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.GPhqluMBhCeTnyNJ]{First Knight}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E98mVLZgE8bX5vQW]{Hatred (Beastmen)} and @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.E98mVLZgE8bX5vQW]{Hatred (Mutants)} Talents.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.Esy17RVOZQw2gShT]{Knight of the Inner Circle}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.vMYEkrWj0ip6ZOdv]{Resistance (Mutations)} Talent.</p>\n<p><strong>Heraldry:</strong> Blue and Gold, Panther Sigil.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>6. Grand Order of the Reiksguard</h3>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FrPCbQ7fq1Fchthn]{Squire}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Empire)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FhK6JOd3LSTlHwoa]{Knight}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.rOPmyLWa37e7s9v6]{Melee (Basic)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.GPhqluMBhCeTnyNJ]{First Knight}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.J9MK0AIaTbvd5oF6]{Drilled} Talent.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.Esy17RVOZQw2gShT]{Knight of the Inner Circle}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.talents.x8g3U68oi8XzWiYr]{Commanding Presence} Talent.</p>\n<p><strong>Heraldry:</strong> White and Red, The Emperor&rsquo;s sigil.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>7. Templars of the Everlasting Light</h3>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FrPCbQ7fq1Fchthn]{Squire}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.DRO5DLF6UcfkvNSh]{Lore (Verena)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.FhK6JOd3LSTlHwoa]{Knight}:</strong> You gain the @Compendium[wfrp4e-core.skills.Lst4xxUcxTYMlD3U]{Melee (Two-Handed)} Skill.</p>\n<p><strong>@Compendium[wfrp4e-core.careers.GPhqluMBhCeTnyNJ]{First Knight}:</strong> You